Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.560
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:03.560 --> 00:00:04.850
- Good afternoon.

00:00:04.850 --> 00:00:07.010
I'm Tomiko Brown-Nagin,
the dean of the Radcliffe

00:00:07.010 --> 00:00:10.940
Institute for Advanced
Study at Harvard University.

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:14.000
Welcome to our annual
Julia S. Phelps Lecture

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:16.760
in the Arts and Humanities.

00:00:16.760 --> 00:00:20.060
Julia Phelps was a
Radcliffe College alumna

00:00:20.060 --> 00:00:23.380
and beloved teacher in
Harvard's German department

00:00:23.380 --> 00:00:27.350
and the Harvard Extension
School and here at Radcliffe.

00:00:27.350 --> 00:00:29.360
When Julia retired
from Radcliffe,

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:32.000
her family, friends,
and colleagues

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.620
established the Phelps
Lecture Series in her honor.

00:00:36.620 --> 00:00:40.070
I'm delighted that Julia's
daughter and son-in-law, Susan

00:00:40.070 --> 00:00:43.790
Napier and Steven Coit
are joining us today.

00:00:43.790 --> 00:00:45.870
Welcome.

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:49.590
I'm also pleased to welcome
Kim Yonghyon, the consul

00:00:49.590 --> 00:00:53.640
general of the Republic
of Korea in Boston.

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:55.980
And I want to acknowledge
Kate Gellert, who's

00:00:55.980 --> 00:01:00.990
here today, the entire Gellert
family, the Radcliffe Institute

00:01:00.990 --> 00:01:04.590
Leadership Society, and all
our generous annual donors who

00:01:04.590 --> 00:01:06.390
support the institute's work.

00:01:06.390 --> 00:01:07.980
Thank you.

00:01:07.980 --> 00:01:12.180
In a moment, I'll introduce our
Phelps lecturer, Min Jin Lee.

00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:14.640
But first, let me
extend one more special

00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:18.630
welcome to Min's husband,
mother, father, and two

00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:19.710
sisters.

00:01:19.710 --> 00:01:22.390
I'm delighted to have you here.

00:01:22.390 --> 00:01:27.070
Min Jin Lee is an acclaimed
novelist, essayist,

00:01:27.070 --> 00:01:28.830
and literary critic.

00:01:28.830 --> 00:01:31.380
She's the author of
two bestselling novels,

00:01:31.380 --> 00:01:34.380
Free Food for
Millionaires, and Pachinko,

00:01:34.380 --> 00:01:37.230
which was a finalist for
the National Book Award.

00:01:37.230 --> 00:01:41.910
Min is currently at work on her
third novel, American Hagwon,

00:01:41.910 --> 00:01:43.920
while in residence
here at Radcliffe

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:50.280
as our inaugural Catherine A.
and Mary C. Gellert fellow.

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:54.000
American Hagwon will complete
Min's thematic trilogy

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:55.680
on the Korean diaspora.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:59.610
And it'll be the central
focus of her work today.

00:01:59.610 --> 00:02:02.550
Min is a part of the
diaspora that she

00:02:02.550 --> 00:02:04.620
chronicles in her novels.

00:02:04.620 --> 00:02:08.820
She moved from Seoul to Queens,
New York as a seven-year-old.

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:12.870
From a young age, Min
found refuge in literature.

00:02:12.870 --> 00:02:15.410
And she has said it was the
writings of the novelist

00:02:15.410 --> 00:02:21.360
Sinclair Lewis that inspired her
to attend Yale, his alma mater.

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:23.670
Despite that
inspiration, it never

00:02:23.670 --> 00:02:26.690
occurred to Min that
she could be a writer.

00:02:26.690 --> 00:02:30.315
A working class Korean-American
and couldn't pursue that path,

00:02:30.315 --> 00:02:32.430
or so she thought.

00:02:32.430 --> 00:02:34.800
She went on to study
history at Yale

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:37.950
and earned her law
degree from Georgetown.

00:02:37.950 --> 00:02:42.150
So how did Min
become a novelist?

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:45.180
To understand Min as a
writer is to understand

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:48.050
how Pachinko came to be.

00:02:48.050 --> 00:02:51.630
Two years into a promising
career as a corporate lawyer,

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:55.470
Min quit because of a
serious liver disease.

00:02:55.470 --> 00:02:59.040
As she tells it, it was
facing this illness that

00:02:59.040 --> 00:03:01.860
inspired her to write fiction.

00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:05.010
She soon set out to
document the Korean diaspora

00:03:05.010 --> 00:03:07.890
in Japan, a community
that she had first

00:03:07.890 --> 00:03:10.470
learned about in college.

00:03:10.470 --> 00:03:13.980
Min spent the next two-plus
decades, on and off,

00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:15.930
writing the story
that eventually

00:03:15.930 --> 00:03:18.240
would become Pachinko.

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:21.630
Along the way, she worked,
much like an academic

00:03:21.630 --> 00:03:26.250
or a journalist, reading widely
across sociology, history,

00:03:26.250 --> 00:03:29.340
political science,
law, and economics.

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:32.310
She drafted an
entire manuscript.

00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:36.930
Then she put it aside,
dissatisfied with result.

00:03:36.930 --> 00:03:40.200
At this impasse, Min
began a new book project

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:42.690
on the Korean
diaspora in America,

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:45.390
which evolved into
her debut novel, Free

00:03:45.390 --> 00:03:47.670
Food for Millionaires.

00:03:47.670 --> 00:03:51.960
It tells the story of Casey Han,
a young, Ivy-League-educated

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:55.260
Korean-American from
Queens, who aspires

00:03:55.260 --> 00:03:57.960
to a glamorous
Manhattan lifestyle

00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:00.390
that she can't afford.

00:04:00.390 --> 00:04:03.060
Through Casey's
story, Min explores

00:04:03.060 --> 00:04:07.080
how conventional ideas of
money, class, and ambition

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:10.950
may fall flat in lived reality.

00:04:10.950 --> 00:04:14.220
After the release of Free
Food for Millionaires,

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:17.940
Min moved with her husband
and their son to Tokyo

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:22.410
and returned to her book
about ethnic Koreans in Japan.

00:04:22.410 --> 00:04:26.970
Dozens of interviews conducted
across Japan compelled Min

00:04:26.970 --> 00:04:30.480
to toss out virtually
all of her earlier draft

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:34.140
and to rewrite Pachinko.

00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:39.420
Released in 2017, Pachinko
was an instant hit.

00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:41.940
It's a sweeping
yet intimate work

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:44.460
of historical fiction
that chronicles

00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:48.000
four generations of triumphs,
tragedies, and everything

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.260
in between as experienced
by a Korean family living

00:04:52.260 --> 00:04:55.500
as perpetual outsiders in Japan.

00:04:55.500 --> 00:04:58.110
Like Free Food for
Millionaires, it's

00:04:58.110 --> 00:05:02.130
rigorously researched,
yet wonderfully readable.

00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:05.250
NPR described Pachinko
as "the kind of book

00:05:05.250 --> 00:05:07.680
that can open your
eyes and fill them

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:10.860
with tears at the same time."

00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:15.690
The story is animated by a
defiant opening sentence.

00:05:15.690 --> 00:05:19.650
"History has failed
us, but no matter."

00:05:19.650 --> 00:05:22.500
Unusual for a
novelist, Min calls

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:27.310
the first line in each of her
novels her thesis statement.

00:05:27.310 --> 00:05:29.710
This reflects her
research-driven approach

00:05:29.710 --> 00:05:33.160
and her keen awareness
of the power of fiction

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:37.780
to reveal complexities,
to tell important truths,

00:05:37.780 --> 00:05:41.070
and to make arguments,
as any lawyer would.

00:05:41.070 --> 00:05:46.360
For Min illuminating themes of
homeland and exile, of identity

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:49.510
and belonging, and of
love and forgiveness

00:05:49.510 --> 00:05:53.470
necessitates the coexistence
of many, often contradictory

00:05:53.470 --> 00:05:55.040
perspectives.

00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:58.000
These perspectives are
articulated by her characters

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.520
and omniscient narration.

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:05.810
Min's craft is scholarly,
interdisciplinary, ambitious,

00:06:05.810 --> 00:06:07.250
and creative.

00:06:07.250 --> 00:06:10.020
She's a natural fit for
Radcliffe's fellowship cohort,

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:13.520
which spans academic
disciplines, the creative arts,

00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:15.080
and professional fields.

00:06:15.080 --> 00:06:18.890
I'm thrilled to have
her among us this year.

00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:22.100
In a moment, I'll turn
things over to Min.

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:25.040
Following her talk, Min
will engage in conversation

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:27.830
with my colleague
Jeannie Suk Gersen, who

00:06:27.830 --> 00:06:31.790
is the John H. Watson, Jr.
professor of Law at Harvard Law

00:06:31.790 --> 00:06:33.260
School.

00:06:33.260 --> 00:06:38.060
Like Min, Jeannie immigrated
to Queens as a young child.

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:39.860
Jeannie has said
that her own family

00:06:39.860 --> 00:06:42.290
experience with
immigration and exile,

00:06:42.290 --> 00:06:46.910
from North and South Korea, has
informed her career, including

00:06:46.910 --> 00:06:50.900
her pathbreaking legal
scholarship on trauma.

00:06:50.900 --> 00:06:53.000
After Jeannie and
Min's conversation,

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.140
we'll open the floor
to your questions.

00:06:55.140 --> 00:06:57.650
Thank you, Jeannie, for
being with us today.

00:06:57.650 --> 00:07:01.340
And now, please join me
in giving a warm welcome

00:07:01.340 --> 00:07:02.420
to Min Jin Lee.

