00:10:50.390 --> 00:10:55.420
Now, in March of 1976,
my mother, and my father,

00:10:55.420 --> 00:10:59.200
and my two sisters and I
immigrated to this country.

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:02.860
And back in Korea, my father
was a marketing executive

00:11:02.860 --> 00:11:06.820
for a cosmetics company, and my
mother was a neighborhood piano

00:11:06.820 --> 00:11:09.040
teacher.

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:11.280
And my father was
born, and he was

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:14.970
raised in Wonsan, which is
a northeastern part of what

00:11:14.970 --> 00:11:17.690
is now considered North Korea.

00:11:17.690 --> 00:11:20.940
And he became a war refuge
when he was 16 years old,

00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:23.280
losing his entire family.

00:11:23.280 --> 00:11:25.680
My mother grew up
in Pusan, which

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:29.310
is a southernmost tip of
what is now South Korea.

00:11:29.310 --> 00:11:33.570
But when they were children,
there was only one Korea.

00:11:33.570 --> 00:11:37.620
Now, I mention the fact that
these two separate republics

00:11:37.620 --> 00:11:42.690
were formed in 1948 because
it's a material fact.

00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:44.520
Now, for their
married life, they

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:48.010
lived in Seoul, where my
sisters and I were born.

00:11:48.010 --> 00:11:50.770
I was about 7 and
1/2 when we left.

00:11:50.770 --> 00:11:55.900
And I recall our modest,
middle class home in Sudogwon,

00:11:55.900 --> 00:11:57.850
in the Mope district.

00:11:57.850 --> 00:12:02.290
It was an ordinary middle class
house with a stone facade.

00:12:02.290 --> 00:12:06.400
It wasn't large, and it wasn't
very special in its appearance.

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:10.300
And these standalone houses
are mostly gone now in Seoul.

00:12:10.300 --> 00:12:13.750
And they've been replaced by
these huge, large apartment

00:12:13.750 --> 00:12:15.190
buildings.

00:12:15.190 --> 00:12:17.380
And that's too bad
because I would

00:12:17.380 --> 00:12:20.720
like to see my old house again.

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:23.690
When I recall my
childhood in Korea,

00:12:23.690 --> 00:12:28.490
I remember the sound of piano
playing, the loud plunking

00:12:28.490 --> 00:12:32.690
of enthusiastic children who
tried to please my mother,

00:12:32.690 --> 00:12:36.710
who is a very gentle person
and a very fine musician.

00:12:36.710 --> 00:12:41.180
And I never once heard her
raise her voice at her students.

00:12:41.180 --> 00:12:44.460
And I think her
students loved her.

00:12:44.460 --> 00:12:49.450
And sometimes when
she wasn't teaching,

00:12:49.450 --> 00:12:52.195
I could hear her play
Haydn and Mozart.

00:12:58.160 --> 00:13:00.960
I remember the smells.

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:03.120
There was a time when
my mother decided

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:06.450
to learn how to make cakes
with her best friend.

00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:08.490
And during this
marvelous period,

00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:13.500
I recall the gorgeous scents of
eggs, and butter, and vanilla.

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:16.710
And it made a really
happy impression on me.

00:13:16.710 --> 00:13:18.450
And I remember the tastes.

00:13:18.450 --> 00:13:21.150
At Christmas, my
mother would have

00:13:21.150 --> 00:13:25.530
a Christmas party, serving ice
cream to all of her students.

00:13:25.530 --> 00:13:27.870
My younger sister sang,
and I couldn't attend

00:13:27.870 --> 00:13:29.460
because we were too little.

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:31.970
So we were sent off
to our uncle's house.

00:13:31.970 --> 00:13:34.470
And we would eat lots
and lots of tangerines

00:13:34.470 --> 00:13:37.910
until we almost got sick.

00:13:37.910 --> 00:13:41.430
And we would watch television
until it was very late.

00:13:41.430 --> 00:13:44.240
I attended the local
elementary school.

00:13:44.240 --> 00:13:47.250
And I was the tallest
child in the class,

00:13:47.250 --> 00:13:49.590
for both boys and girls.

00:13:49.590 --> 00:13:52.290
And everybody was
seated in size order,

00:13:52.290 --> 00:13:54.660
so I would sit all
the way in the back.

00:13:54.660 --> 00:13:57.630
And I had a tendency
to daydream,

00:13:57.630 --> 00:14:00.150
so I was not a
very good student.

00:14:00.150 --> 00:14:03.630
Whenever I was bored, I would
just get up from my seat

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:05.760
and try to wander.

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:07.670
I hardly spoke.

00:14:07.670 --> 00:14:09.640
And I had no friends.

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:14.670
And I did not have the words
to speak to other children.

00:14:14.670 --> 00:14:17.160
And I think in retrospect,
I must have had

00:14:17.160 --> 00:14:19.200
some sort of learning issue.

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:22.140
However, back then
in Korea, a child

00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:27.700
like me was just
considered slow or odd.

00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:31.510
I was profoundly unaware
of my social environment,

00:14:31.510 --> 00:14:35.620
and I could not accurately
perceive social cues

00:14:35.620 --> 00:14:38.380
of my teachers or my peers.

00:14:38.380 --> 00:14:41.860
And one day, when I
was in the first grade,

00:14:41.860 --> 00:14:45.880
and I was six years old,
I completed my assignment.

00:14:45.880 --> 00:14:49.090
And needing to move,
I got up from my seat,

00:14:49.090 --> 00:14:53.600
and I walked to and fro in
the back of the classroom.

00:14:53.600 --> 00:14:56.620
And my teacher called
my name and told

00:14:56.620 --> 00:14:59.560
me to come to the
front of the classroom.

00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:01.540
So I went.

00:15:01.540 --> 00:15:06.160
And she told me to hold
out my hands like this.

00:15:06.160 --> 00:15:10.490
And I had no idea what
she was going to do.

00:15:10.490 --> 00:15:14.400
She picked up a ruler
and she struck my hands.

00:15:14.400 --> 00:15:16.830
And I don't recall
how many times,

00:15:16.830 --> 00:15:19.170
but it was more than once.

00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:21.580
I don't recall if it hurt.

00:15:21.580 --> 00:15:24.600
Mostly, I remember
being surprised,

00:15:24.600 --> 00:15:28.180
and I felt ashamed of myself.

00:15:28.180 --> 00:15:31.770
And later, the teacher
called my mother

00:15:31.770 --> 00:15:34.810
and asked her to come in.

00:15:34.810 --> 00:15:37.780
And to this day, I don't
know what they discussed.

00:15:40.330 --> 00:15:45.040
But I suppose it must have had
something to do with the fact

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:47.560
that I was not a good learner.

00:15:47.560 --> 00:15:51.060
My mother worked all the
time, teaching piano.

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:55.780
So the day my mother came to
school to talk with my teacher,

00:15:55.780 --> 00:15:59.020
it felt like a very
special day because we

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:01.300
could go home together.

00:16:01.300 --> 00:16:04.480
And after talking to
my teacher, my mother

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:07.720
took me to a cafe
near the school,

00:16:07.720 --> 00:16:10.780
and she bought me
a piece of pastry.

00:16:10.780 --> 00:16:15.000
She wasn't upset
with me, not at all.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.540
My mother just said that
I should remain in my seat

00:16:18.540 --> 00:16:22.140
until my teacher
allowed me to move.

00:16:22.140 --> 00:16:26.010
So in school, I always
tried to do that.

00:16:26.010 --> 00:16:26.740
I still do.

00:16:26.740 --> 00:16:28.672
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:30.610 --> 00:16:34.770
So those are a few of my
very persistent memories

00:16:34.770 --> 00:16:36.960
of my childhood in Korea.

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:39.720
And I share them with
you today because writers

00:16:39.720 --> 00:16:44.700
need their memories the way
mathematicians need logic.

00:16:44.700 --> 00:16:48.650
I have written about
Koreans for most of my life.

00:16:48.650 --> 00:16:52.340
And I've been asked why
I write about Koreans.

00:16:52.340 --> 00:16:56.540
And it seems like such a
strange question to me.

00:16:56.540 --> 00:17:00.770
Because why wouldn't
I write about Koreans?

00:17:00.770 --> 00:17:04.880
To me, Koreans are
mothers, and fathers,

00:17:04.880 --> 00:17:11.890
and daughters, and sons, which
means Koreans are like us.

00:17:11.890 --> 00:17:17.520
We are worthy of
consideration and reflection.

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:21.450
About a year and a half
ago, a European journalist

00:17:21.450 --> 00:17:22.650
interviewed me.

00:17:22.650 --> 00:17:25.920
And he asked me this question.

00:17:25.920 --> 00:17:28.541
What are Koreans like?

00:17:28.541 --> 00:17:30.961
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:32.900 --> 00:17:35.920
What are Koreans like?

00:17:35.920 --> 00:17:38.490
Now, the journalist meant well.

00:17:38.490 --> 00:17:40.840
And I work as a
journalist sometimes.

00:17:40.840 --> 00:17:43.220
And I know that we can
fumble with our words,

00:17:43.220 --> 00:17:47.770
even though we're supposed to
know them better than most.

00:17:47.770 --> 00:17:51.580
I think he was trying
to help Koreans, help

00:17:51.580 --> 00:17:54.430
us tell our side
of the story, so he

00:17:54.430 --> 00:18:00.690
was asking a writer of Korean
ethnicity to explain my tribe.

00:18:00.690 --> 00:18:04.170
And as you know, if
and whenever Korea

00:18:04.170 --> 00:18:07.740
is discussed in the media,
especially in the mainstream

00:18:07.740 --> 00:18:11.100
news, it is so
often about that one

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:14.820
young Korean man
from the North who

00:18:14.820 --> 00:18:18.210
is trying to hold
onto his power and is

00:18:18.210 --> 00:18:22.320
taking desperate measures
in order to do so.

00:18:22.320 --> 00:18:26.500
And he does this much in
the vein of his father

00:18:26.500 --> 00:18:29.590
and his grandfather have done.

00:18:29.590 --> 00:18:33.550
So his story is a story
of a dynasty, which

00:18:33.550 --> 00:18:36.610
means that you know
that at its root

00:18:36.610 --> 00:18:40.560
it is a story about a family.

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:45.620
People around the world who
want to see more of Koreans

00:18:45.620 --> 00:18:48.670
get such a small
and dark window.

00:18:48.670 --> 00:18:51.260
And that is, indeed, a shame.

00:18:51.260 --> 00:18:56.010
So what are Koreans like?

00:18:56.010 --> 00:19:00.030
I thought about the
immensity of this question,

00:19:00.030 --> 00:19:04.920
the fallacy behind it, and
the overwhelming likelihood

00:19:04.920 --> 00:19:08.610
of falling into stereotypes
in answering him.

00:19:08.610 --> 00:19:13.050
And yet, not to reply
would have been rude,

00:19:13.050 --> 00:19:15.840
because I had spent some
time with this journalist.

00:19:15.840 --> 00:19:18.600
And I knew he was
not a bad person.

00:19:18.600 --> 00:19:21.480
So I answered him.

00:19:21.480 --> 00:19:25.297
I told him the Koreans
liked to dance.

00:19:25.297 --> 00:19:28.706
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:32.602 --> 00:19:35.530
Dance.

00:19:35.530 --> 00:19:38.050
I was only half kidding.

00:19:38.050 --> 00:19:41.669
Three months ago, I turned 50.

00:19:41.669 --> 00:19:42.960
It's hard to believe, isn't it?

00:19:42.960 --> 00:19:44.672
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:44.672 --> 00:19:48.160
And because I write
so much about Koreans

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:50.590
and have done so
for so many decades,

00:19:50.590 --> 00:19:55.060
I have now encountered thousands
of Koreans around the world.

00:19:55.060 --> 00:19:58.210
And wherever I go,
I do my best to take

00:19:58.210 --> 00:20:03.160
the temperature of Koreans
from every age and group.

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:05.920
So if you follow
Koreans in the news,

00:20:05.920 --> 00:20:09.040
you can find some
widespread generalizations

00:20:09.040 --> 00:20:11.140
about the peninsula
and its people.

00:20:11.140 --> 00:20:12.760
And they go like this.

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:16.380
You will know that there
was a miracle on the Han,

00:20:16.380 --> 00:20:21.400
a phrase used to explain South
Korea's incredible, superhuman

00:20:21.400 --> 00:20:25.510
economic success as it
emerged from a catastrophic,

00:20:25.510 --> 00:20:29.230
post-colonial, post-war
poverty, and all

00:20:29.230 --> 00:20:31.700
in a matter of a few decades.

00:20:31.700 --> 00:20:35.420
Koreans are global leaders in
internet speed, shipbuilding,

00:20:35.420 --> 00:20:38.600
steel, the manufacture
of consumer electronics,

00:20:38.600 --> 00:20:42.230
automobiles, memory
chips, and semiconductors.

00:20:42.230 --> 00:20:45.470
South Korea leads the
PISA scores, literacy,

00:20:45.470 --> 00:20:47.630
secondary and
tertiary education.

00:20:47.630 --> 00:20:51.860
And Korea has produced world
class athletes, filmmakers,

00:20:51.860 --> 00:20:54.450
musicians, and artists.

00:20:54.450 --> 00:20:57.580
South Koreans also
have the highest rates

00:20:57.580 --> 00:21:02.430
in plastic surgery, suicide,
cryptocurrency speculation,

00:21:02.430 --> 00:21:08.140
youth dissatisfaction,
and elderly poverty.

00:21:08.140 --> 00:21:13.900
And for North Korea, according
to the 2018 Global Slavery

00:21:13.900 --> 00:21:19.660
Index, North Korea has the
highest number of slaves today.

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:24.020
Today, 1 out of every 10
North Korean citizens--

00:21:24.020 --> 00:21:27.250
that is 2.6 million people--

00:21:27.250 --> 00:21:30.580
live under slavery conditions.

00:21:30.580 --> 00:21:34.930
It can be argued very
logically and fairly that,

00:21:34.930 --> 00:21:38.770
because all of its citizens
lack the freedom of movement,

00:21:38.770 --> 00:21:43.720
even at the very highest levels,
almost 26 million North Koreans

00:21:43.720 --> 00:21:48.370
are actually hostages
to one leader.

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:51.590
So whether it's the number
of churches being built,

00:21:51.590 --> 00:21:54.670
the number of
speedskating gold medals,

00:21:54.670 --> 00:21:57.940
or noses being reconstructed,
or the trafficking

00:21:57.940 --> 00:22:02.260
of human beings, Koreans
hold top positions

00:22:02.260 --> 00:22:04.422
on important lists.

00:22:04.422 --> 00:22:09.140
But Koreans like to dance.

00:22:09.140 --> 00:22:12.110
And if you go to
festivals or weddings,

00:22:12.110 --> 00:22:18.810
you will see Korean grandmothers
moving their arms elegantly,

00:22:18.810 --> 00:22:24.570
and swaying their
shoulders and their heads.

00:22:24.570 --> 00:22:28.864
Koreans have
excellent rhythm, Ani.

00:22:28.864 --> 00:22:30.030
That's a little inside joke.

00:22:30.030 --> 00:22:32.220
[LAUGHS]

00:22:32.220 --> 00:22:33.750
Koreans can be funny.

00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:35.280
We like to sing.

00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:36.710
And we love to eat.

00:22:36.710 --> 00:22:39.550
And we like a little dazzle.

00:22:39.550 --> 00:22:42.640
And if you know a bit
about the Korean psyche,

00:22:42.640 --> 00:22:45.600
you know that we're known
for carrying this thing,

00:22:45.600 --> 00:22:50.410
this feeling called han,
defined as a specific kind

00:22:50.410 --> 00:22:54.550
of inexpressible anguish that
comes from having suffered

00:22:54.550 --> 00:22:57.010
collectively as a people.

00:22:57.010 --> 00:23:00.820
And then there's nunchi, a
kind of emotional intelligence,

00:23:00.820 --> 00:23:04.680
or the ability to
perceive subtext.

00:23:04.680 --> 00:23:08.850
And there's also the concept of
jeong, my favorite, the quality

00:23:08.850 --> 00:23:13.320
of affection and attachment
that people develop with time

00:23:13.320 --> 00:23:15.830
and common experience.

00:23:15.830 --> 00:23:24.820
Now, my job as a writer demands
that I avoid generalizations.

00:23:24.820 --> 00:23:28.900
But I fear that the very
prevalent generalizations

00:23:28.900 --> 00:23:32.980
are so limited and negative
that I am anxious as

00:23:32.980 --> 00:23:35.860
to how to correct
misrepresentations

00:23:35.860 --> 00:23:40.000
and distortions of my
community of origin

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:43.580
and my diasporic community.

00:23:43.580 --> 00:23:48.810
In my experience, the Koreans
that I know are very romantic.

00:23:48.810 --> 00:23:52.340
They are full of
love and intensity.

00:23:52.340 --> 00:23:55.500
And they're physical
in their expression.

00:23:55.500 --> 00:23:58.460
So I want you to know that too.

00:23:58.460 --> 00:24:02.610
Now, I was a lawyer before
I began writing fiction.

00:24:02.610 --> 00:24:05.950
And I majored in history, and
then I went to law school.

00:24:05.950 --> 00:24:09.940
And I don't have a degree
in English or an MFA.

00:24:09.940 --> 00:24:15.150
It took me 11 years to write and
ultimately sell my first novel,

00:24:15.150 --> 00:24:17.100
called Free Food
for Millionaires.

00:24:17.100 --> 00:24:20.770
And it was a book about Koreans
in America, specifically

00:24:20.770 --> 00:24:24.760
in New York City, where
class and money define

00:24:24.760 --> 00:24:30.950
a specific reality with
hidden rules for outsiders.

00:24:30.950 --> 00:24:33.140
I wrote that book
because I wanted

00:24:33.140 --> 00:24:37.070
to understand where
poor Koreans fit in

00:24:37.070 --> 00:24:40.130
and what it would
mean for a poor Korean

00:24:40.130 --> 00:24:44.750
to be accepted into an
elite Ivy League institution

00:24:44.750 --> 00:24:48.470
and try to have bigger
dreams than the ones laid out

00:24:48.470 --> 00:24:50.960
by her parents.

00:24:50.960 --> 00:24:55.430
Another 10 years passed
before I published Pachinko,

00:24:55.430 --> 00:24:58.800
a book about Koreans in Japan.

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:02.400
Among many things, I
wanted to understand

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:05.190
the modern 20th century Korean.

00:25:05.190 --> 00:25:08.250
And I knew that I could
not understand her

00:25:08.250 --> 00:25:13.860
unless I located her position
in the colonial history of Japan

00:25:13.860 --> 00:25:18.030
and Korea and how that
post-colonial history informed

00:25:18.030 --> 00:25:20.900
the Korean population in Japan.

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:24.920
So now, to complete my
trilogy of the diaspora, which

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:29.210
I'm calling The
Koreans, I wanted

00:25:29.210 --> 00:25:34.370
to know what is the most
important value for Koreans,

00:25:34.370 --> 00:25:37.750
not just in Korea,
but around the world.

00:25:37.750 --> 00:25:40.990
And I sensed what it was.

00:25:40.990 --> 00:25:43.990
Koreans value education.

00:25:43.990 --> 00:25:47.350
They value it like nothing else.

00:25:47.350 --> 00:25:49.930
For Koreans, since
the Silla Kingdom,

00:25:49.930 --> 00:25:54.010
when national exams were first
administered to candidates

00:25:54.010 --> 00:25:58.180
to become bureaucrats, Koreans
have regarded education

00:25:58.180 --> 00:26:02.860
as a gateway and a path
to progress, distinction,

00:26:02.860 --> 00:26:06.100
and proof of one's value.

00:26:06.100 --> 00:26:10.240
Kingdoms have risen
and fallen in Korea,

00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:14.890
this peninsula attached to
China, located east of Japan

00:26:14.890 --> 00:26:17.330
and south of Russia.

00:26:17.330 --> 00:26:19.670
The nation was
colonized by Japan

00:26:19.670 --> 00:26:21.860
and then later split
by foreign powers.

00:26:21.860 --> 00:26:25.730
And then from 1950 to
1953, not a long time

00:26:25.730 --> 00:26:29.750
ago, the two Koreas
fought a civil war,

00:26:29.750 --> 00:26:36.680
which killed 2 million Korean
men, women, and children,

00:26:36.680 --> 00:26:43.570
over 600,000 Chinese, and
over 50,000 Americans.

00:26:43.570 --> 00:26:46.690
And as you know, although
the armistice agreement

00:26:46.690 --> 00:26:51.340
was signed in July of 1953,
there has been a ceasefire,

00:26:51.340 --> 00:26:55.290
but the war has not ended.

00:26:55.290 --> 00:26:58.500
The ancient civilized
nation, which

00:26:58.500 --> 00:27:04.650
is now made up of two republics,
each only 71 years old,

00:27:04.650 --> 00:27:09.210
has suffered through dictators,
the repression of human rights,

00:27:09.210 --> 00:27:13.020
the systematic torture and
murder of university students

00:27:13.020 --> 00:27:15.210
and labor organizers.

00:27:15.210 --> 00:27:17.400
And many South Korean
business leaders

00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:21.300
have done incredibly good
things for their nations.

00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:25.220
And others have sought
only personal gain

00:27:25.220 --> 00:27:28.340
and profited through corruption.

00:27:28.340 --> 00:27:32.900
South Korea is growing up to
be a great democratic nation,

00:27:32.900 --> 00:27:36.410
as evidenced by the recent
Candlelight Revolution, where

00:27:36.410 --> 00:27:43.010
several months, from 2016 to
2017, collectively, millions

00:27:43.010 --> 00:27:45.830
of South Korean
citizens gathered week

00:27:45.830 --> 00:27:49.640
after week, effectively
and peacefully,

00:27:49.640 --> 00:27:52.500
and ousted a corrupt regime.

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:55.890
South Korean citizens
uphold and honor

00:27:55.890 --> 00:27:58.770
a long history of protest.

00:27:58.770 --> 00:28:01.350
And they have excellent
voting turnout

00:28:01.350 --> 00:28:07.270
and are deeply engaged in the
formation of their democracy.

00:28:07.270 --> 00:28:10.120
Both Koreas are global players.

00:28:10.120 --> 00:28:14.800
South Korea is a member
of the OECD and the G20,

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:18.520
as evidence of its status
as an advanced economy.

00:28:18.520 --> 00:28:21.640
It is the 12th largest
economy in the world.

00:28:21.640 --> 00:28:24.920
And North Korea insists on
taking the center stage.

00:28:24.920 --> 00:28:29.770
And in a few weeks,
the American president

00:28:29.770 --> 00:28:35.200
will meet with him in Vietnam
for their second summit.

00:28:35.200 --> 00:28:38.650
How did Koreans
become global players?

00:28:38.650 --> 00:28:41.310
And how did it happen so fast?

00:28:41.310 --> 00:28:44.000
And if you ask Koreans
around the world,

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:47.140
nearly everyone will
mention that Koreans

00:28:47.140 --> 00:28:49.930
are willing to figure
things out and they

00:28:49.930 --> 00:28:52.600
will work around rigid systems.

00:28:52.600 --> 00:28:53.440
We will read.

00:28:53.440 --> 00:28:54.130
We will study.

00:28:54.130 --> 00:28:56.320
We will try to solve problems.

00:28:56.320 --> 00:28:59.660
Koreans will go to great
lengths to learn more.

00:28:59.660 --> 00:29:06.020
In short, Koreans care
immensely about education.

00:29:06.020 --> 00:29:09.780
Well, education
is a vital subject

00:29:09.780 --> 00:29:11.700
to every living creature.

00:29:11.700 --> 00:29:15.720
So from birth, every
infant has to learn skills.

00:29:15.720 --> 00:29:20.490
And gradually, if she has the
necessary biological capacity,

00:29:20.490 --> 00:29:23.800
she will learn how to hold
her head up, and crawl,

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:26.780
and express herself.

00:29:26.780 --> 00:29:30.670
And eventually, she will
need to learn enough skills

00:29:30.670 --> 00:29:34.450
to be independent and
productive for herself

00:29:34.450 --> 00:29:36.530
and for her community.

00:29:36.530 --> 00:29:38.530
So if everyone
needs an education,

00:29:38.530 --> 00:29:41.800
then how is the modern
Korean's value of education

00:29:41.800 --> 00:29:44.260
different than,
let's say, someone

00:29:44.260 --> 00:29:48.550
from Spain, or Palestine,
or Syria, or Ghana,

00:29:48.550 --> 00:29:50.740
or New Zealand?

00:29:50.740 --> 00:29:54.580
Well, we can measure
the unique interest

00:29:54.580 --> 00:29:58.240
in terms of sheer
investment, in terms of time,

00:29:58.240 --> 00:30:01.060
in terms of money or output.

00:30:01.060 --> 00:30:06.350
We can look at it through the
lens of culture or history.

00:30:06.350 --> 00:30:11.180
Now, from its Confucian roots
for well over 1,000 years,

00:30:11.180 --> 00:30:14.450
Koreans have trusted
that one's status in life

00:30:14.450 --> 00:30:18.530
can be improved markedly
by educational achievement.

00:30:18.530 --> 00:30:23.900
By passing exams, one can attain
a position near the ruler,

00:30:23.900 --> 00:30:28.430
become a political
leader, or serve one.

00:30:28.430 --> 00:30:32.210
And he can acquire status,
privilege, and security

00:30:32.210 --> 00:30:37.160
for himself, his family,
and his descendants.

00:30:37.160 --> 00:30:40.850
Well, a millennia of
social conditioning

00:30:40.850 --> 00:30:44.300
is hard to shake off.

00:30:44.300 --> 00:30:48.320
Despite the calamities that
Korea has suffered, or perhaps

00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:52.580
because of the calamities that
Koreans have endured, even as

00:30:52.580 --> 00:30:58.320
recently as the Asian financial
crisis and the IMF bailout,

00:30:58.320 --> 00:31:03.630
education has become even
more valued in South Korea.

00:31:03.630 --> 00:31:07.110
In South Korea today, it is not
sufficient to send one's child

00:31:07.110 --> 00:31:07.970
to school.

00:31:07.970 --> 00:31:09.180
No.

00:31:09.180 --> 00:31:11.880
Rather, the child
will begin to get

00:31:11.880 --> 00:31:15.540
supplemental education,
private tutoring,

00:31:15.540 --> 00:31:18.280
starting at the age of four.

00:31:18.280 --> 00:31:19.960
South Korean high
school students

00:31:19.960 --> 00:31:23.410
sleep on average
five hours a day,

00:31:23.410 --> 00:31:26.200
which means some sleep less.

00:31:26.200 --> 00:31:30.200
And when they are awake,
they are studying.

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:32.310
Why?

00:31:32.310 --> 00:31:36.480
Every year, the college
entrance exam, called the CSAT,

00:31:36.480 --> 00:31:40.500
or the [INAUDIBLE] is
offered exactly once

00:31:40.500 --> 00:31:42.960
on a date in November.

00:31:42.960 --> 00:31:48.540
And 600,000 South Korean
students take this exam.

00:31:48.540 --> 00:31:51.090
And the score that she
receives will determine where

00:31:51.090 --> 00:31:54.290
she can apply and be admitted.

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:56.510
The top three
universities are widely

00:31:56.510 --> 00:32:00.930
believed to be Seoul National,
Korea, and Yonsei University.

00:32:00.930 --> 00:32:06.800
And the initials SKY,
making up the acronym SKY,

00:32:06.800 --> 00:32:08.630
reaching for the sky--

00:32:08.630 --> 00:32:12.620
the metaphor is not
lost on this crowd.

00:32:12.620 --> 00:32:20.210
And of the 600,000 examinees,
there about 11,000 spots.

00:32:20.210 --> 00:32:24.440
So only 2% can attend
the SKY schools.

00:32:24.440 --> 00:32:27.410
And to be sure,
not every examinee

00:32:27.410 --> 00:32:30.020
wants to attend a SKY school.

00:32:30.020 --> 00:32:35.780
Last year, about 108,000
applied to those three schools.

00:32:35.780 --> 00:32:39.840
And whether or not this
is an objective reality,

00:32:39.840 --> 00:32:43.590
the overwhelming majority
of the entire country

00:32:43.590 --> 00:32:48.900
believes that SKY graduates
are the most desirable.

00:32:48.900 --> 00:32:52.320
SKY graduates and
their alumni networks

00:32:52.320 --> 00:32:55.890
dominate the most prestigious
companies and government

00:32:55.890 --> 00:32:57.210
positions.

00:32:57.210 --> 00:33:00.660
And also keep in mind that
the youth unemployment

00:33:00.660 --> 00:33:04.740
in South Korea is hovering
officially around 9%.

00:33:04.740 --> 00:33:08.920
But because so many have
given up seeking employment,

00:33:08.920 --> 00:33:11.550
most economists and
sociologists believe

00:33:11.550 --> 00:33:14.940
that it's well over 20%.

00:33:14.940 --> 00:33:18.960
So if you are a
Korean parent, and you

00:33:18.960 --> 00:33:23.410
want to help your
child, what do you do?

00:33:23.410 --> 00:33:28.790
What would you do to help your
child to be part of the 2%?

00:33:28.790 --> 00:33:32.030
If you have the means, you
may try to get your child out

00:33:32.030 --> 00:33:33.780
of South Korea.

00:33:33.780 --> 00:33:38.150
And this is precisely what many
South Koreans attempt to do.

00:33:38.150 --> 00:33:41.250
They send their children
abroad at various stages

00:33:41.250 --> 00:33:43.730
so they can avoid the
intense and suffocating

00:33:43.730 --> 00:33:47.000
examination-based
paths to getting

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.730
a university-level education.

00:33:49.730 --> 00:33:55.390
And maybe, if that is not an
option for you, what do you do?

00:33:55.390 --> 00:34:00.250
But more likely than not,
nearly every South Korean parent

00:34:00.250 --> 00:34:05.380
of every socioeconomic
level sends her child

00:34:05.380 --> 00:34:07.760
through hagwons.

00:34:07.760 --> 00:34:11.870
A hagwon-- H-A-G-W-O-N--

00:34:11.870 --> 00:34:17.150
is the Korean word for a
for-profit tutoring business,

00:34:17.150 --> 00:34:21.860
a place to receive private
supplemental education.

00:34:21.860 --> 00:34:26.659
There are hagwons in South
Korea to study anything.

00:34:26.659 --> 00:34:30.270
You can find a hagwon to
study any language, any exam,

00:34:30.270 --> 00:34:34.969
and even non-academic fields
like Model UN, debate,

00:34:34.969 --> 00:34:41.900
video gaming, or even how to
boost your child's creativity.

00:34:41.900 --> 00:34:44.929
And if you think about
it, private tutors

00:34:44.929 --> 00:34:47.239
have always existed.

00:34:47.239 --> 00:34:51.560
Universal public education,
or compulsory education,

00:34:51.560 --> 00:34:54.810
is a modern concept
for many countries,

00:34:54.810 --> 00:34:56.810
including the
United States, which

00:34:56.810 --> 00:35:00.980
still varies its requirements
from state to state.

00:35:00.980 --> 00:35:03.920
In the United States,
we have Stanley Kaplan,

00:35:03.920 --> 00:35:05.390
or Princeton Review.

00:35:05.390 --> 00:35:07.640
Those are our national hagwons.

00:35:07.640 --> 00:35:09.290
And for elementary
school levels,

00:35:09.290 --> 00:35:11.780
there's Kumon, a
Japanese export,

00:35:11.780 --> 00:35:16.270
where children can start as
young as three years old,

00:35:16.270 --> 00:35:18.590
in America.

00:35:18.590 --> 00:35:21.530
In South Korea, we
can safely assume

00:35:21.530 --> 00:35:23.450
that the average
Korean household

00:35:23.450 --> 00:35:25.640
income is somewhere
between $20,000

00:35:25.640 --> 00:35:29.360
$30,000, depending
upon your calculation.

00:35:29.360 --> 00:35:33.960
So if you spend $300 a month
for your four-year-old,

00:35:33.960 --> 00:35:38.510
and if you continue to
pay $3,600 per annum--

00:35:38.510 --> 00:35:41.270
and this amount will only
increase every single year

00:35:41.270 --> 00:35:44.720
dramatically because she
will need other subjects,

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:47.460
and there will be
tuition for high school--

00:35:47.460 --> 00:35:51.780
you are spending a significant
portion of your income

00:35:51.780 --> 00:35:57.910
over the lifetime of your child
for supplemental education.

00:35:57.910 --> 00:36:02.510
Now, my third novel, which I'm
researching and writing here,

00:36:02.510 --> 00:36:05.110
and it is about the value
of education for Koreans

00:36:05.110 --> 00:36:06.360
around the world.

00:36:06.360 --> 00:36:11.160
And I'm interested in what
an education should mean.

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:13.360
And at this stage
in my life, I am

00:36:13.360 --> 00:36:18.190
interested in the metaphysical
question of wisdom.

00:36:18.190 --> 00:36:20.890
How can I live a wise life?

00:36:20.890 --> 00:36:23.110
What is a wise life?

00:36:23.110 --> 00:36:27.745
And how is education
different than wisdom?

00:36:27.745 --> 00:36:29.770
So how do I work?

00:36:29.770 --> 00:36:32.520
How do I write a novel?

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:36.187
When I write fiction,
I do a lot of research.

00:36:36.187 --> 00:36:37.770
And I look at the
relevant scholarship

00:36:37.770 --> 00:36:40.740
in the fields of economics,
anthropology, law, education,

00:36:40.740 --> 00:36:43.710
sociology, psychology,
and history.

00:36:43.710 --> 00:36:46.770
And then I review the
traditional mainstream media.

00:36:46.770 --> 00:36:50.430
And concurrently, I interview
hundreds of people and conduct

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:51.840
site visits.

00:36:51.840 --> 00:36:54.930
And for this book, I
have just done fieldwork

00:36:54.930 --> 00:36:58.830
in New York, Seoul, Jeju,
Los Angeles, and London.

00:36:58.830 --> 00:37:01.710
And I will head to Australia
and New Zealand for the summer

00:37:01.710 --> 00:37:04.560
because these
English-speaking countries are

00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:08.340
among the many places that South
Koreans send their children

00:37:08.340 --> 00:37:10.390
to learn English.

00:37:10.390 --> 00:37:13.070
And this past December,
I was in Seoul

00:37:13.070 --> 00:37:14.720
with two of my
research partners,

00:37:14.720 --> 00:37:17.180
where I had the chance
to meet with hagwon

00:37:17.180 --> 00:37:20.870
owners, private tutors,
parents, school teachers,

00:37:20.870 --> 00:37:23.490
and all kinds of students.

00:37:23.490 --> 00:37:25.850
I've met with
[INAUDIBLE] fathers.

00:37:25.850 --> 00:37:28.010
And these are fathers
who live in Seoul,

00:37:28.010 --> 00:37:30.320
or who live somewhere
in South Korea.

00:37:30.320 --> 00:37:33.470
And they send their money abroad
to their wives and children

00:37:33.470 --> 00:37:36.500
who are studying
outside of South Korea.

00:37:36.500 --> 00:37:38.960
I have met homestay guardians.

00:37:38.960 --> 00:37:41.360
These are Koreans who
serve as guardians

00:37:41.360 --> 00:37:42.980
for parachute children.

00:37:42.980 --> 00:37:45.860
And parachute children are
kids who are dropped off

00:37:45.860 --> 00:37:49.120
in foreign countries to study.

00:37:49.120 --> 00:37:51.520
I visited
international students,

00:37:51.520 --> 00:37:54.250
international schools,
and cafes where

00:37:54.250 --> 00:37:58.660
students go to avoid
studying, universities,

00:37:58.660 --> 00:38:00.690
international school fairs.

00:38:00.690 --> 00:38:02.680
And I've been to goshitels.

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:06.910
Goshitels are cheap hotels
where students in South Korea

00:38:06.910 --> 00:38:09.430
live in windowless rooms.

00:38:09.430 --> 00:38:13.350
That's about 40 square feet.

00:38:13.350 --> 00:38:18.570
I have visited a K-pop museum,
internet cafes called PCBang's,

00:38:18.570 --> 00:38:22.550
and many, many, many hagwons.

00:38:22.550 --> 00:38:26.090
In the United States, I have
met their American counterparts

00:38:26.090 --> 00:38:27.800
and talked with
admissions officers

00:38:27.800 --> 00:38:31.490
from universities
like Yale and Harvard,

00:38:31.490 --> 00:38:34.220
admissions officers of
elite private schools,

00:38:34.220 --> 00:38:36.320
and interviewed
college presidents.

00:38:36.320 --> 00:38:39.440
And this past October, I
attended the Harvard admissions

00:38:39.440 --> 00:38:40.930
trial.

00:38:40.930 --> 00:38:42.820
And I mentioned
some of my research.

00:38:42.820 --> 00:38:47.320
Because doing this kind of
work, as I write and rewrite

00:38:47.320 --> 00:38:51.950
a work of fiction, humbles me.

00:38:51.950 --> 00:38:55.250
It teaches me to listen more.

00:38:55.250 --> 00:38:58.490
Reality corrects
my preconceptions.

00:38:58.490 --> 00:39:03.560
And my eyes and my ears
experience what my characters

00:39:03.560 --> 00:39:05.840
may ultimately feel.

00:39:05.840 --> 00:39:09.620
Now, it may be true that a
Korean child studies from dawn

00:39:09.620 --> 00:39:14.210
to dusk and that a Korean
parent may impoverish himself

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:16.740
to support his child's studies.

00:39:16.740 --> 00:39:19.910
And when I share
some of what I learn,

00:39:19.910 --> 00:39:25.370
I noticed that people seem
alarmed at my findings.

00:39:25.370 --> 00:39:28.790
And sometimes I
share your alarm.

00:39:28.790 --> 00:39:33.530
However, I've noticed that
every single Korean I've

00:39:33.530 --> 00:39:38.030
spoken with has specific
wishes and reasons.

00:39:38.030 --> 00:39:40.370
So I try never to judge.

00:39:40.370 --> 00:39:46.770
I try to ask more questions, and
I consider his point of view.

00:39:46.770 --> 00:39:52.050
I worry a great deal about
how Koreans are perceived,

00:39:52.050 --> 00:39:54.900
not because I think
Koreans are ideal.

00:39:54.900 --> 00:39:57.510
No, far from it.

00:39:57.510 --> 00:40:01.770
I worry because when I encounter
the way Koreans are perceived

00:40:01.770 --> 00:40:05.700
in the world by non-Koreans
and diasporic Koreans,

00:40:05.700 --> 00:40:10.440
I find that the Koreans don't
get to tell their full story.

00:40:10.440 --> 00:40:12.780
And I'm hoping
that you and I can

00:40:12.780 --> 00:40:16.530
be more fair if we realize
the Koreans have achieved

00:40:16.530 --> 00:40:20.730
impressive outcomes and they
care intensely about education

00:40:20.730 --> 00:40:22.485
because they have good reason.

00:40:25.170 --> 00:40:27.090
Why?

00:40:27.090 --> 00:40:31.460
Why do Koreans care so
much about education?

00:40:31.460 --> 00:40:38.270
Well, one reason is that
Koreans want power no less

00:40:38.270 --> 00:40:40.970
than any of us in this room.

00:40:40.970 --> 00:40:43.760
Koreans want power because
the average Korean,

00:40:43.760 --> 00:40:47.000
whether she lives
in Pusan or Toronto,

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:51.680
may feel less than powerful.

00:40:51.680 --> 00:40:55.160
And who among us would
deny that we sometimes

00:40:55.160 --> 00:40:59.180
feel less than powerful
and that sometimes life can

00:40:59.180 --> 00:41:02.090
feel like a dead end?

00:41:02.090 --> 00:41:04.900
So I ask myself,
what will a mother

00:41:04.900 --> 00:41:07.990
do when she wants
her child to have

00:41:07.990 --> 00:41:11.630
a little more than she has?

00:41:11.630 --> 00:41:14.630
And how is she
different from me?

00:41:14.630 --> 00:41:18.050
And how is she
different from us?

00:41:18.050 --> 00:41:23.120
I am overwhelmed by the
complexity of my subject,

00:41:23.120 --> 00:41:25.070
and because I
realize that I am not

00:41:25.070 --> 00:41:29.120
writing about education,
the diaspora, or Koreans,

00:41:29.120 --> 00:41:30.930
I'm writing about humans.

00:41:30.930 --> 00:41:33.990
And we are very complicated.

00:41:33.990 --> 00:41:35.460
We are vulnerable.

00:41:35.460 --> 00:41:38.550
We are needy, and
we are frightened.

00:41:38.550 --> 00:41:43.300
We make terrible choices,
and we live with regrets.

00:41:43.300 --> 00:41:47.740
And more often than not, we
cannot give voice to our most

00:41:47.740 --> 00:41:50.570
important feelings.

00:41:50.570 --> 00:41:55.250
When I teach writing, I set
ground rules in my classroom.

00:41:55.250 --> 00:41:58.300
We will respect each
other's privacy,

00:41:58.300 --> 00:42:00.590
and we will
encourage each other.

00:42:00.590 --> 00:42:04.570
Because we are writers and we
are developing our stories.

00:42:04.570 --> 00:42:07.520
The quest is for
each writer to work

00:42:07.520 --> 00:42:10.310
on her most important
questions, even

00:42:10.310 --> 00:42:16.010
if her questions are strange,
embarrassing, or peculiar.

00:42:16.010 --> 00:42:18.320
Because her most
important questions

00:42:18.320 --> 00:42:22.900
will allow her to
finish her work.

00:42:22.900 --> 00:42:27.590
I want to know what drew
my writer to her subject.

00:42:27.590 --> 00:42:32.120
And more than that, I want my
writer to own her questions.

00:42:32.120 --> 00:42:34.370
And through her
process of writing,

00:42:34.370 --> 00:42:38.600
I want the writer
to own her answers.

00:42:38.600 --> 00:42:45.590
Because I believe that, as a
society, we need these answers.

00:42:45.590 --> 00:42:47.870
When the European
journalist asked

00:42:47.870 --> 00:42:53.260
me the question, what
are Koreans like, what

00:42:53.260 --> 00:42:58.060
I heard in his question
was really the question,

00:42:58.060 --> 00:43:01.240
are Koreans human.

00:43:01.240 --> 00:43:03.680
Are they like me?

00:43:03.680 --> 00:43:09.300
So I had told him that
Koreans like to dance.

00:43:09.300 --> 00:43:15.800
And here, let me explain
more fully what I meant.

00:43:15.800 --> 00:43:20.670
Dance is a physical
allegory of our emotions.

00:43:20.670 --> 00:43:23.970
Our bodies are telling
our hearts' stories

00:43:23.970 --> 00:43:26.250
without using words.

00:43:26.250 --> 00:43:29.430
I told the journalist that
Koreans like to dance because I

00:43:29.430 --> 00:43:34.140
wanted him to understand that
a Korean cannot always say what

00:43:34.140 --> 00:43:39.330
she means, and she cannot always
sit still until she is told she

00:43:39.330 --> 00:43:40.900
can move.

00:43:40.900 --> 00:43:45.160
Dance requires twists
and gestures, backward

00:43:45.160 --> 00:43:47.450
and forward motion.

00:43:47.450 --> 00:43:52.800
Dance requires reaching,
and stretching, and bending.

00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:56.460
And dance allows some
freedom of desire

00:43:56.460 --> 00:43:59.470
and the manifestation of will.

00:43:59.470 --> 00:44:01.210
Perhaps the journalist
thought that I

00:44:01.210 --> 00:44:04.810
was alluding to the
extraordinary choreography

00:44:04.810 --> 00:44:08.020
and the dramatic execution
of synchronized movements

00:44:08.020 --> 00:44:09.850
of K-pop.

00:44:09.850 --> 00:44:10.510
I was not.

00:44:10.510 --> 00:44:12.730
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:12.730 --> 00:44:15.730
I was talking
about the old woman

00:44:15.730 --> 00:44:20.770
who wants to roll her shoulders
while closing her eyes.

00:44:20.770 --> 00:44:25.240
I am writing,
though I'm a writer.

00:44:25.240 --> 00:44:28.900
Why am I talking about dancing?

00:44:28.900 --> 00:44:31.720
I am talking about
ordinary people

00:44:31.720 --> 00:44:37.060
dancing because I worry that
the literate and the elite,

00:44:37.060 --> 00:44:40.060
the ones who have
the fancy words,

00:44:40.060 --> 00:44:44.020
are the only ones who
get to be considered.

00:44:44.020 --> 00:44:49.990
And if you think about that,
it is both absurd and immoral.

00:44:49.990 --> 00:44:54.550
Less than 100 years ago,
nearly all the women in Korea

00:44:54.550 --> 00:44:56.780
were illiterate.

00:44:56.780 --> 00:45:00.110
In my mind, I was
thinking, why is it

00:45:00.110 --> 00:45:04.560
that the poor, old, Korean
woman likes to dance?

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:06.680
Why is that?

00:45:06.680 --> 00:45:09.620
Perhaps, despite all
the constrictions

00:45:09.620 --> 00:45:14.090
of a nation geographically
bound by superpowers

00:45:14.090 --> 00:45:17.470
and culturally bound
by ancient precepts,

00:45:17.470 --> 00:45:21.590
and despite all the
difficulties of a people who've

00:45:21.590 --> 00:45:26.600
been scattered around the
globe, Koreans from many corners

00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:30.890
like to dance
because we are human,

00:45:30.890 --> 00:45:35.250
and our physical bodies
crave expression.

00:45:35.250 --> 00:45:40.300
Even with the fear of censure,
and the fear of shame,

00:45:40.300 --> 00:45:46.060
and the fear of exclusion, we
will express ourselves fully,

00:45:46.060 --> 00:45:48.942
even if it is for
just one dance.

00:45:48.942 --> 00:45:53.110
And we will do it with rhythm.

00:45:53.110 --> 00:45:56.700
More than our spectacular
accomplishments

00:45:56.700 --> 00:46:00.900
or our catastrophic
failures, perhaps

00:46:00.900 --> 00:46:06.870
it is our daily bodies, our
yearnings, our very weakness,

00:46:06.870 --> 00:46:11.330
and our wish for expression
that makes us human.

00:46:11.330 --> 00:46:15.310
And I hope that is what
I will carry with me as I

00:46:15.310 --> 00:46:18.499
continue to write about us.

00:46:18.499 --> 00:46:19.996
Thank you.

00:46:19.996 --> 00:46:23.489
[APPLAUSE]

00:46:41.135 --> 00:46:42.510
I'm so glad you're
here, Jeannie.

00:46:42.510 --> 00:46:44.630
[LAUGHS]

00:46:44.630 --> 00:46:46.130
- I'm so glad I'm here too.

00:46:46.130 --> 00:46:48.830
- It's scary being up there.

00:46:48.830 --> 00:46:51.050
- So it's really amazing.

00:46:51.050 --> 00:46:53.630
I've often said to
Min Jin that I really

00:46:53.630 --> 00:46:56.550
feel like we were twins
separated at birth because we

00:46:56.550 --> 00:46:57.050
have--

00:46:57.050 --> 00:46:58.466
- Well, your mom
and dad are here.

00:46:58.466 --> 00:47:01.806
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:01.806 --> 00:47:03.680
- There are so
many things that we

00:47:03.680 --> 00:47:07.910
have had in common, including
the hometown of Wonsan

00:47:07.910 --> 00:47:11.690
and many, many things.

00:47:11.690 --> 00:47:15.290
And I want to say,
first of all, I

00:47:15.290 --> 00:47:17.240
am amazed that you're
writing about hagwon.

00:47:17.240 --> 00:47:22.790
It's kind of one of these shady
secrets that Koreans have.

00:47:22.790 --> 00:47:24.230
- I like hagwons.

00:47:24.230 --> 00:47:25.850
- Yeah.

00:47:25.850 --> 00:47:28.430
And I will come out and
say for the first time,

00:47:28.430 --> 00:47:31.940
in front of a public
audience, I attended hagwon

00:47:31.940 --> 00:47:37.040
when I was five years old and
going forward until probably--

00:47:37.040 --> 00:47:39.770
- Your mom was just trying
to show her support.

00:47:39.770 --> 00:47:40.270
- Yeah.

00:47:40.270 --> 00:47:42.470
But in the American
culture in which

00:47:42.470 --> 00:47:51.380
we operate, this idea, this
ethnically inflected, private,

00:47:51.380 --> 00:47:56.870
after school venues
in which Asians

00:47:56.870 --> 00:48:02.900
go to do more than what they
do in school, and probably

00:48:02.900 --> 00:48:07.650
in these windowless
rooms, in basements,

00:48:07.650 --> 00:48:12.720
so that they can pass
these standardized tests

00:48:12.720 --> 00:48:17.580
and, in fact, score as
well as they possibly can,

00:48:17.580 --> 00:48:19.230
there is something
very, I think,

00:48:19.230 --> 00:48:22.735
stigmatized in our culture
about that phenomenon.

00:48:22.735 --> 00:48:23.780
- In Western culture.

00:48:23.780 --> 00:48:24.280
- Yeah.

00:48:24.280 --> 00:48:25.732
- In Korea, it's really normal.

00:48:25.732 --> 00:48:26.940
If you didn't send your kid--

00:48:26.940 --> 00:48:27.790
- It's very normal.

00:48:27.790 --> 00:48:29.460
- --to hagwon,
you'd be a weirdo.

00:48:29.460 --> 00:48:30.420
- Yeah.

00:48:30.420 --> 00:48:33.960
But in the United States,
it's not something

00:48:33.960 --> 00:48:39.480
that, even as a person who was
a member of an elite university,

00:48:39.480 --> 00:48:41.790
a faculty member or
a student, it's not

00:48:41.790 --> 00:48:45.330
something you openly bandy about
as something you're proud of.

00:48:45.330 --> 00:48:45.870
- Oh.

00:48:45.870 --> 00:48:48.030
- And I just think that
it's really amazing that

00:48:48.030 --> 00:48:51.240
you're writing about this
because we need to know more

00:48:51.240 --> 00:48:54.330
about what is up
with these hagwon,

00:48:54.330 --> 00:48:58.890
and how do they fit into
our Korean-American,

00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:03.570
Asian-American, and just
American educational landscape.

00:49:03.570 --> 00:49:04.570
What do they mean?

00:49:04.570 --> 00:49:07.230
What are they about?

00:49:07.230 --> 00:49:09.930
What is the stigma around them?

00:49:09.930 --> 00:49:15.870
And what is it that makes them
just kind of vexing phenomena?

00:49:15.870 --> 00:49:18.270
- Well, I actually like hagwons.

00:49:18.270 --> 00:49:20.561
And the more I study them,
the more I like them.

00:49:20.561 --> 00:49:22.560
And it's kind of curious
because you would think

00:49:22.560 --> 00:49:24.030
that I would dislike them.

00:49:24.030 --> 00:49:25.860
But I've met so
many people who've

00:49:25.860 --> 00:49:27.630
gone to hagwons all their lives.

00:49:27.630 --> 00:49:31.260
And now I realized, it's
not just for studying.

00:49:31.260 --> 00:49:33.641
It's actually almost
like a community center.

00:49:33.641 --> 00:49:34.140
- For sure.

00:49:34.140 --> 00:49:36.930
- It also serves as
a daycare function,

00:49:36.930 --> 00:49:39.390
which is really important
to recognize for working

00:49:39.390 --> 00:49:41.340
women and working men.

00:49:41.340 --> 00:49:43.380
So when I was just
recently in Los Angeles,

00:49:43.380 --> 00:49:46.542
I went to this entire area where
you have all these strip malls.

00:49:46.542 --> 00:49:48.000
And then you have,
like, let's say,

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:49.950
the pizza store, the drugstore.

00:49:49.950 --> 00:49:51.900
And you'll have this
weird looking building,

00:49:51.900 --> 00:49:54.000
and it'll have kind of
blacked out windows,

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:56.370
with children looking sort
of happy, but I don't know.

00:49:56.370 --> 00:49:57.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:57.910 --> 00:50:01.310
And there'll be all
these buses in the front.

00:50:01.310 --> 00:50:03.030
And it turns out
that these buses

00:50:03.030 --> 00:50:07.770
pick up the children after
school and bring them back in.

00:50:07.770 --> 00:50:10.890
And the kids stay at these
hagwons from 3 o'clock

00:50:10.890 --> 00:50:14.940
until, let's say, 6:30 until
their parents pick them up.

00:50:14.940 --> 00:50:18.270
And the parents pay
about $300 a month.

00:50:18.270 --> 00:50:21.750
And that means that if
the parent is working

00:50:21.750 --> 00:50:24.840
when the school is off, for
a public school especially,

00:50:24.840 --> 00:50:26.800
well, what's a
working parent to do?

00:50:26.800 --> 00:50:29.880
And we know that in this
country, we don't have daycare.

00:50:29.880 --> 00:50:31.930
So I was actually
quite happy with it.

00:50:31.930 --> 00:50:34.770
And these kids were not studying
a lot, especially the ones

00:50:34.770 --> 00:50:35.711
in LA.

00:50:35.711 --> 00:50:36.210
I mean--

00:50:36.210 --> 00:50:37.620
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:37.620 --> 00:50:39.150
They were not studying.

00:50:39.150 --> 00:50:41.072
They were, you know, chatting.

00:50:41.072 --> 00:50:42.780
- I, too, used to play
hooky from hagwon.

00:50:42.780 --> 00:50:43.471
- Right.

00:50:43.471 --> 00:50:43.970
right.

00:50:43.970 --> 00:50:46.200
Yeah, I met some really
impressive people in London

00:50:46.200 --> 00:50:47.460
when I was doing fieldwork.

00:50:47.460 --> 00:50:49.560
And I said, so did
you go to hagwon?

00:50:49.560 --> 00:50:51.710
And this seemed like a
very attractive Korean man.

00:50:51.710 --> 00:50:53.070
He's like, in this 30s.

00:50:53.070 --> 00:50:54.362
You would hire him in a minute.

00:50:54.362 --> 00:50:55.861
And I said, so did
you go to hagwon?

00:50:55.861 --> 00:50:56.920
He was like, yeah.

00:50:56.920 --> 00:50:58.170
And I said, did you like them?

00:50:58.170 --> 00:50:59.253
He was like, I loved them.

00:50:59.253 --> 00:51:01.320
And I said, why?

00:51:01.320 --> 00:51:04.020
And he said, well, because
on Wednesdays and Thursdays,

00:51:04.020 --> 00:51:07.144
I would play hooky, and I
would see all my friends.

00:51:07.144 --> 00:51:09.060
And we would go to
PCBang's, and we would just

00:51:09.060 --> 00:51:11.730
basically play video
games and eat [INAUDIBLE]..

00:51:11.730 --> 00:51:14.580
And I was like, OK, I get it.

00:51:14.580 --> 00:51:16.770
And it turned out the
teachers would sort of

00:51:16.770 --> 00:51:19.470
turn a blind eye
because they knew

00:51:19.470 --> 00:51:21.461
that these kids needed a break.

00:51:21.461 --> 00:51:22.960
And then I realized,
like, no, these

00:51:22.960 --> 00:51:24.320
are very human institutions.

00:51:24.320 --> 00:51:27.700
So we have all this data, like
oh, kids study 18 hours a day.

00:51:27.700 --> 00:51:30.760
And some kids are studying
18 hours a day, absolutely.

00:51:30.760 --> 00:51:33.880
But for the most part,
there's a lot of hooky.

00:51:33.880 --> 00:51:36.185
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:37.570 --> 00:51:41.560
- I wanted to return to
two different statements

00:51:41.560 --> 00:51:45.460
that you made that juxtaposed
next to each other,

00:51:45.460 --> 00:51:49.070
I just thought maybe
would be revealing.

00:51:49.070 --> 00:51:53.260
One was that you said
that reality corrects

00:51:53.260 --> 00:51:56.320
my preconceptions,
that as you learn more,

00:51:56.320 --> 00:52:00.550
you have these preconceived
ideas, they change as a result.

00:52:00.550 --> 00:52:01.300
- Right.

00:52:01.300 --> 00:52:03.700
- The other is
the idea that when

00:52:03.700 --> 00:52:05.920
you describe the research
that you've been doing

00:52:05.920 --> 00:52:10.420
and the findings, some of
which you shared with us today,

00:52:10.420 --> 00:52:15.126
they are alarming, possibly to
you and possibly to the people

00:52:15.126 --> 00:52:16.250
who are hearing about them.

00:52:16.250 --> 00:52:19.160
Certainly, some of
them alarmed me.

00:52:19.160 --> 00:52:19.835
- Yeah.

00:52:19.835 --> 00:52:22.750
No, the Western audience,
like, that's crazy.

00:52:22.750 --> 00:52:23.830
These people are crazy.

00:52:23.830 --> 00:52:25.960
They often say things like,
these people are crazy.

00:52:25.960 --> 00:52:27.490
And then I kind of
think, actually,

00:52:27.490 --> 00:52:29.698
if you spent, like, six
hours with them, you wouldn't

00:52:29.698 --> 00:52:31.040
think that they're crazy.

00:52:31.040 --> 00:52:33.750
- Yeah, so what is this
relationship between feeling

00:52:33.750 --> 00:52:38.970
like your preconceptions are
changed by more reality, more,

00:52:38.970 --> 00:52:41.860
let's say, field work, more
talking to these people,

00:52:41.860 --> 00:52:45.270
and really learning about
what motivates them,

00:52:45.270 --> 00:52:49.980
and the idea that what is
happening as you do learn more

00:52:49.980 --> 00:52:52.350
is that things get
even more alarming,

00:52:52.350 --> 00:52:57.960
and that they are even more
surprising, and possibly

00:52:57.960 --> 00:52:59.581
less reassuring?

00:52:59.581 --> 00:53:00.080
- Yes.

00:53:00.080 --> 00:53:02.970
I did have this one thing where
I interviewed a really, really

00:53:02.970 --> 00:53:05.220
fancy hagwon tutor.

00:53:05.220 --> 00:53:07.230
And she teaches SATs.

00:53:07.230 --> 00:53:08.310
And she's very private.

00:53:08.310 --> 00:53:09.330
And I talked to her.

00:53:09.330 --> 00:53:13.170
And she worked--
she went to Harvard.

00:53:13.170 --> 00:53:15.852
And she worked at Goldman Sachs.

00:53:15.852 --> 00:53:18.599
[LAUGHS]

00:53:18.599 --> 00:53:20.140
And then now, she's
a hagwon teacher,

00:53:20.140 --> 00:53:21.910
and she makes a lot of dough.

00:53:21.910 --> 00:53:22.970
And I was talking to her.

00:53:22.970 --> 00:53:23.710
I liked her.

00:53:23.710 --> 00:53:25.550
She was really kind
of cool and fun.

00:53:25.550 --> 00:53:27.640
And if I needed a kid--

00:53:27.640 --> 00:53:29.844
if I had a kid who
needed SAT tutoring,

00:53:29.844 --> 00:53:31.510
I could kind of see
why I would hire her

00:53:31.510 --> 00:53:33.190
because she just
seemed really relatable

00:53:33.190 --> 00:53:34.930
and kind of no nonsense.

00:53:34.930 --> 00:53:36.820
But at the same time,
I'm kind of thinking,

00:53:36.820 --> 00:53:39.490
you went to Harvard, and you're
working at Goldman Sachs.

00:53:39.490 --> 00:53:40.780
And she had a baby.

00:53:40.780 --> 00:53:43.270
And I said, so did you send
your daughter to hagwon?

00:53:43.270 --> 00:53:45.280
And she said, yes.

00:53:45.280 --> 00:53:48.520
And because I had the data
point already that 85%

00:53:48.520 --> 00:53:51.546
of four-year-olds in South Korea
start hagwons, I was like--

00:53:51.546 --> 00:53:52.170
I kind of knew.

00:53:52.170 --> 00:53:54.005
I was like, maybe
four, maybe five.

00:53:54.005 --> 00:53:55.630
But then again, she's
a hagwon teacher.

00:53:55.630 --> 00:53:58.812
Maybe she's kind of
like, I'm so above this.

00:53:58.812 --> 00:54:00.520
I said, when did you
start your daughter?

00:54:00.520 --> 00:54:03.725
She said, age two.

00:54:03.725 --> 00:54:04.600
And I was like, damn.

00:54:04.600 --> 00:54:06.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:06.130 --> 00:54:07.520
Seriously?

00:54:07.520 --> 00:54:11.790
And of course, I try to
be a good ethnographer.

00:54:11.790 --> 00:54:15.280
And I said, for what?

00:54:15.280 --> 00:54:17.080
And she said, well,
she was trying

00:54:17.080 --> 00:54:18.310
to get into a pre-school.

00:54:18.310 --> 00:54:20.226
It was really hard to
get into this preschool,

00:54:20.226 --> 00:54:23.890
so she had private consulting.

00:54:23.890 --> 00:54:24.910
And I said, OK.

00:54:24.910 --> 00:54:27.020
So like, this is a
situation where I'm alarmed,

00:54:27.020 --> 00:54:29.770
because I'm kind of thinking,
you have your shit together.

00:54:29.770 --> 00:54:31.390
Why would you need this?

00:54:31.390 --> 00:54:33.970
And she doesn't need daycare
because she has money.

00:54:33.970 --> 00:54:35.496
But she said it's
because she had

00:54:35.496 --> 00:54:37.120
to get into a certain
kind of preschool

00:54:37.120 --> 00:54:38.536
because this
preschool is a feeder

00:54:38.536 --> 00:54:40.430
for a certain kindergarten.

00:54:40.430 --> 00:54:43.390
And so she had a
[INAUDIBLE] of a consultant

00:54:43.390 --> 00:54:45.340
who knew about this school.

00:54:45.340 --> 00:54:46.960
And it was like $60 a thing.

00:54:46.960 --> 00:54:49.810
And I said, so what did they do?

00:54:49.810 --> 00:54:53.010
And she said, well, you'll
have, let's say, a pizza,

00:54:53.010 --> 00:54:54.250
kind of like a wooden pizza.

00:54:54.250 --> 00:54:56.080
And you cut out little
sections, and you

00:54:56.080 --> 00:54:57.220
learn about percentages.

00:54:57.220 --> 00:54:59.740
And I was like, oh, OK.

00:54:59.740 --> 00:55:02.897
And also how to hold
a writing implement,

00:55:02.897 --> 00:55:05.230
that was apparently something
that people get tested on.

00:55:08.640 --> 00:55:11.612
But again, if you hung out
with her, you'd like her.

00:55:11.612 --> 00:55:13.820
This is the thing I really
want to make as a defense.

00:55:13.820 --> 00:55:17.660
Because we have this tendency
to say, that's crazy.

00:55:17.660 --> 00:55:18.980
Why would you do that?

00:55:18.980 --> 00:55:20.396
But you hang out
with them, you're

00:55:20.396 --> 00:55:22.700
going like, yeah, I guess
I could kind of see that.

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:26.390
- Well, this process
of moving from empathy

00:55:26.390 --> 00:55:30.020
to a real sense of
alienation, like,

00:55:30.020 --> 00:55:32.630
I can't possibly
imagine why someone

00:55:32.630 --> 00:55:34.970
would do that, that must be
a really interesting process

00:55:34.970 --> 00:55:39.080
for you as a writer who, I
think throughout your talk,

00:55:39.080 --> 00:55:47.690
you occupied both the position
of speaking of Koreans as them

00:55:47.690 --> 00:55:49.920
and also representing an us.

00:55:49.920 --> 00:55:50.420
- Us.

00:55:50.420 --> 00:55:51.380
Yes.

00:55:51.380 --> 00:55:55.490
- And of course, you are also
working across national divides

00:55:55.490 --> 00:55:57.830
like the Koreans in
the United States

00:55:57.830 --> 00:56:00.620
and other nations,
diaspora Koreans,

00:56:00.620 --> 00:56:03.020
versus the ones in Korea.

00:56:03.020 --> 00:56:05.360
And there is a very--

00:56:05.360 --> 00:56:08.559
for lots of people,
a very stark divide.

00:56:08.559 --> 00:56:09.850
- LA Koreans are so different--

00:56:09.850 --> 00:56:10.510
- LA Koreans versus
New York Koreans.

00:56:10.510 --> 00:56:11.593
- --than New York Koreans.

00:56:11.593 --> 00:56:13.430
Oh, my goodness, it's
like different gangs.

00:56:13.430 --> 00:56:15.770
- And the kind of
Koreans who get

00:56:15.770 --> 00:56:19.340
into schools like
Harvard University

00:56:19.340 --> 00:56:23.510
and their perceptions
of the kinds of Koreans

00:56:23.510 --> 00:56:28.340
who don't have what it
takes to get here or we

00:56:28.340 --> 00:56:32.270
don't really work hard, but
we don't have the special--

00:56:32.270 --> 00:56:35.630
you don't have the special
creativity and the innovation

00:56:35.630 --> 00:56:39.680
that Harvard University looks
for in its selection process.

00:56:39.680 --> 00:56:42.080
I think there's so many
different kinds of us

00:56:42.080 --> 00:56:45.107
and them processes
going on within the--

00:56:45.107 --> 00:56:46.190
- Here's a generalization.

00:56:46.190 --> 00:56:47.930
Korean-Canadians, very nice.

00:56:47.930 --> 00:56:50.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:52.571 --> 00:56:54.320
Never met a Korean-Canadian
I didn't like.

00:56:54.320 --> 00:56:57.308
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:58.310 --> 00:57:00.560
- I know.

00:57:00.560 --> 00:57:03.120
So one of the things that I--

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:06.440
I didn't realize until in
the middle of your talk.

00:57:06.440 --> 00:57:09.760
When I saw the title,
Are Koreans Human?

00:57:09.760 --> 00:57:12.500
And I think you told me
that some people said, wow,

00:57:12.500 --> 00:57:14.900
are you getting
pushback because it

00:57:14.900 --> 00:57:18.140
sounds like you're suggesting
they might not be human?

00:57:18.140 --> 00:57:18.650
And--

00:57:18.650 --> 00:57:20.630
- We are.

00:57:20.630 --> 00:57:23.090
- Right, whereas I read
it totally differently

00:57:23.090 --> 00:57:25.830
in that I thought you meant
like, are we superhuman?

00:57:25.830 --> 00:57:26.570
- Right.

00:57:26.570 --> 00:57:27.970
- Not like are we subhuman.

00:57:27.970 --> 00:57:29.570
- You are.

00:57:29.570 --> 00:57:30.620
- No, no.

00:57:30.620 --> 00:57:33.470
But that's how I read
this title, especially

00:57:33.470 --> 00:57:35.430
in light of the
idea of superpowers.

00:57:35.430 --> 00:57:38.960
And of course, now I understand
that part of what you're saying

00:57:38.960 --> 00:57:44.300
is how flanked both the
Korean nation and the culture

00:57:44.300 --> 00:57:48.130
have been by geopolitical
superpowers and how--

00:57:48.130 --> 00:57:49.090
- Which makes Korea--

00:57:49.090 --> 00:57:49.460
right.

00:57:49.460 --> 00:57:50.900
Which makes Koreans
feel like they

00:57:50.900 --> 00:57:54.380
have to kind of be a superpower
in order to deal with the fact

00:57:54.380 --> 00:57:56.270
that, for thousands
of years, you've

00:57:56.270 --> 00:57:59.120
had these superpowers
constantly in their face.

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:03.050
- Right, despite the name
for the country, which

00:58:03.050 --> 00:58:09.860
was the Hermit Kingdom, the idea
that we are so separate that we

00:58:09.860 --> 00:58:12.950
don't mix well with others.

00:58:12.950 --> 00:58:15.200
- You and I mix well.

00:58:15.200 --> 00:58:16.930
- Now, we do.

00:58:16.930 --> 00:58:20.680
And it's also one of the--

00:58:20.680 --> 00:58:23.900
hearing you talk about your
almost mute childhood--

00:58:23.900 --> 00:58:25.700
- Mm-hmm.

00:58:25.700 --> 00:58:27.920
This can be confirmed
by my family.

00:58:27.920 --> 00:58:30.560
I didn't really start talking
until almost middle school.

00:58:30.560 --> 00:58:33.020
- I believe that because
that was the same for me.

00:58:33.020 --> 00:58:33.860
- Right.

00:58:33.860 --> 00:58:36.500
We had rich interior lives.

00:58:36.500 --> 00:58:40.250
- The idea that I'm here
speaking with you to hundreds

00:58:40.250 --> 00:58:42.490
of people, that's insane.

00:58:42.490 --> 00:58:43.520
- Right.

00:58:43.520 --> 00:58:46.280
- Given the way I grew up and
the way I thought of myself.

00:58:46.280 --> 00:58:47.770
- This is actually
virtual reality.

00:58:47.770 --> 00:58:50.150
- Yeah, it can't be real.

00:58:50.150 --> 00:58:52.940
But yeah, I mean, how do you--

00:58:52.940 --> 00:58:57.720
and is that something
about Koreans that--

00:58:57.720 --> 00:58:58.220
- Sure.

00:58:58.220 --> 00:59:02.081
- Because that's how I always
thought about that muteness.

00:59:02.081 --> 00:59:03.580
- But I think a
part of it's Korean.

00:59:03.580 --> 00:59:05.296
But I have two
sisters, and so do you,

00:59:05.296 --> 00:59:07.170
because we were basically
separated at birth.

00:59:07.170 --> 00:59:08.670
- Right.

00:59:08.670 --> 00:59:10.430
- And both my sisters,
all three of us

00:59:10.430 --> 00:59:12.230
didn't speak any English
when we came to this country.

00:59:12.230 --> 00:59:12.750
- Same.

00:59:12.750 --> 00:59:13.250
- Right?

00:59:13.250 --> 00:59:15.050
But my older sister
and my younger sister,

00:59:15.050 --> 00:59:18.320
who I'm going to embarrass right
now, they're wildly popular.

00:59:18.320 --> 00:59:20.060
And they picked up
English immediately.

00:59:20.060 --> 00:59:20.899
They had friends.

00:59:20.899 --> 00:59:22.940
They got tracked into the
smart class right away.

00:59:22.940 --> 00:59:25.790
I was in a dumb
class for two years.

00:59:25.790 --> 00:59:29.540
That's what they literally
called it at PS 102.

00:59:29.540 --> 00:59:31.280
And I just kind
of always thought

00:59:31.280 --> 00:59:33.526
that I would have been
tempted to say it's

00:59:33.526 --> 00:59:34.775
a Korean thing for my silence.

00:59:34.775 --> 00:59:39.840
But because I had evidence in my
house that I was just a loser,

00:59:39.840 --> 00:59:44.060
that it was very--

00:59:44.060 --> 00:59:45.091
I knew that it was me.

00:59:45.091 --> 00:59:46.340
I knew that some of it was me.

00:59:46.340 --> 00:59:48.890
So part of it's a fact
that, of course, in Korean--

00:59:48.890 --> 00:59:50.720
if you look at
Korean fairy tales

00:59:50.720 --> 00:59:54.410
or folktales, the fact the girls
speaking is not necessarily

00:59:54.410 --> 00:59:55.880
a virtue.

00:59:55.880 --> 00:59:58.340
The big virtue for Korean
girls is sacrifice.

00:59:58.340 --> 01:00:00.950
[SNORES]

01:00:00.950 --> 01:00:02.285
Endless fucking sacrifice.

01:00:02.285 --> 01:00:05.120
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:05.120 --> 01:00:06.900
So I really don't like that.

01:00:06.900 --> 01:00:08.090
But I got it.

01:00:08.090 --> 01:00:09.530
I mean, we get the
message, right?

01:00:09.530 --> 01:00:11.738
We get the message that
you're supposed to sacrifice,

01:00:11.738 --> 01:00:12.990
you're supposed to suffer.

01:00:12.990 --> 01:00:16.300
However, as a child, I
think there was something--

01:00:16.300 --> 01:00:17.480
I had something.

01:00:17.480 --> 01:00:19.232
I don't know what it is.

01:00:19.232 --> 01:00:20.690
- But what about
this juxtaposition

01:00:20.690 --> 01:00:28.450
between the extremity of
the educational imperative

01:00:28.450 --> 01:00:31.960
and the extremely high
rates of plastic surgery?

01:00:31.960 --> 01:00:33.867
You mentioned this.

01:00:33.867 --> 01:00:34.825
Is there some relation?

01:00:34.825 --> 01:00:36.550
- Of course.

01:00:36.550 --> 01:00:42.700
- How do you think about both of
those sometimes alarming facts?

01:00:42.700 --> 01:00:44.577
- Well, in Korea--

01:00:44.577 --> 01:00:46.660
I wrote an article about
this for The Chosun Ilbo,

01:00:46.660 --> 01:00:48.550
and I got death threats.

01:00:48.550 --> 01:00:52.960
Because I said that plastic
surgery is an option.

01:00:52.960 --> 01:00:54.340
I am not against it.

01:00:54.340 --> 01:00:56.260
If you want to get
it, that's fine.

01:00:56.260 --> 01:00:57.370
I'm 50.

01:00:57.370 --> 01:01:00.340
I've thought about it.

01:01:00.340 --> 01:01:04.460
Now, having said that,
what I wrote in my article

01:01:04.460 --> 01:01:07.130
for The Chosun
Ilbo was that it's

01:01:07.130 --> 01:01:10.790
something-- it's not really
consent technically if you

01:01:10.790 --> 01:01:12.410
make your child get it.

01:01:12.410 --> 01:01:13.790
Because you're a child.

01:01:13.790 --> 01:01:15.862
So if you tell your
child, you are ugly,

01:01:15.862 --> 01:01:17.570
or you tell your child,
there's something

01:01:17.570 --> 01:01:19.153
wrong with your
eyes-- so for, example

01:01:19.153 --> 01:01:20.960
my eyes are not desirable.

01:01:20.960 --> 01:01:23.180
They're supposed to
have another lid.

01:01:23.180 --> 01:01:25.880
So the most common
surgery for Koreans

01:01:25.880 --> 01:01:27.956
is the eye surgery where
you sort of tuck it in.

01:01:27.956 --> 01:01:30.080
And sometimes, it can turn
out great and sometimes,

01:01:30.080 --> 01:01:31.837
not so much.

01:01:31.837 --> 01:01:33.920
I had a friend of mine who
had her nose done twice

01:01:33.920 --> 01:01:35.480
because it moved.

01:01:35.480 --> 01:01:37.010
And that was kind of a drag.

01:01:37.010 --> 01:01:38.370
And her parents made her do it.

01:01:38.370 --> 01:01:40.670
Her parents literally--
her dad was a psychiatrist.

01:01:40.670 --> 01:01:43.310
And he actually said, there's
something wrong with your nose.

01:01:43.310 --> 01:01:44.460
We have to fix it.

01:01:44.460 --> 01:01:46.040
So they put a bridge in there.

01:01:46.040 --> 01:01:48.800
And I kind of thought, you
know, if your father told you

01:01:48.800 --> 01:01:51.620
that you're ugly, or
that your nose is ugly,

01:01:51.620 --> 01:01:53.140
that's not consent.

01:01:53.140 --> 01:01:54.170
Right?

01:01:54.170 --> 01:01:55.370
I mean, it's like trauma.

01:01:55.370 --> 01:01:59.231
So it is absolutely kind of
a psychological terrorism.

01:01:59.231 --> 01:02:01.730
So I kind of wrote this, saying
that if you wanted to get it

01:02:01.730 --> 01:02:04.730
as an adult, it's absolutely
fine, but as a child,

01:02:04.730 --> 01:02:06.380
I had these reservations.

01:02:06.380 --> 01:02:08.100
Death threats.

01:02:08.100 --> 01:02:09.530
- Death threats from--

01:02:09.530 --> 01:02:11.212
- The comment boxes.

01:02:11.212 --> 01:02:12.920
Like, die, bitch, and
that kind of stuff.

01:02:12.920 --> 01:02:14.539
- From the side of
people who are--

01:02:14.539 --> 01:02:15.830
- That's a death threat, right?

01:02:15.830 --> 01:02:17.060
- People who want--

01:02:17.060 --> 01:02:20.372
people who want to be more
supportive of plastic surgery?

01:02:20.372 --> 01:02:22.205
- I think they're plastic
surgeons, frankly.

01:02:22.205 --> 01:02:25.020
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:25.020 --> 01:02:25.780
I do.

01:02:25.780 --> 01:02:28.260
I mean, it's a billion
dollar industry.

01:02:28.260 --> 01:02:29.510
It makes a ton of money.

01:02:29.510 --> 01:02:31.630
And I'm like-- and I
wasn't saying don't do it.

01:02:31.630 --> 01:02:33.730
I just said, if
kids are doing it,

01:02:33.730 --> 01:02:36.490
and if parents are saying
you need to change,

01:02:36.490 --> 01:02:38.230
that's a different
thing altogether.

01:02:38.230 --> 01:02:40.780
And I think I was kind of
making a legal argument.

01:02:40.780 --> 01:02:43.605
Having said that, the
thing with plastic surgery

01:02:43.605 --> 01:02:44.980
is that if you go
to South Korea,

01:02:44.980 --> 01:02:46.930
people don't really think
of it as necessarily

01:02:46.930 --> 01:02:48.637
moral or immoral.

01:02:48.637 --> 01:02:50.970
They don't even think that
they're trying to be Western.

01:02:50.970 --> 01:02:53.010
- I they think of it
like we think of braces.

01:02:53.010 --> 01:02:53.510
- Right.

01:02:53.510 --> 01:02:54.970
- That is how I experience it.

01:02:54.970 --> 01:02:55.660
- Exactly.

01:02:55.660 --> 01:02:56.610
That's exactly what
they think of it.

01:02:56.610 --> 01:02:57.640
- I think that is
how they think of it.

01:02:57.640 --> 01:02:59.290
- They think of it as a
competitive advantage.

01:02:59.290 --> 01:03:00.710
And I totally understand that.

01:03:00.710 --> 01:03:02.929
And actually, the US is
kind of following Asia.

01:03:02.929 --> 01:03:04.720
Now, I don't know if
you want to know this.

01:03:04.720 --> 01:03:08.840
But LinkedIn, you put
your photograph up there.

01:03:08.840 --> 01:03:09.770
It used to be--

01:03:09.770 --> 01:03:12.920
I mean, in Korea, right now,
if you want to get a job,

01:03:12.920 --> 01:03:17.040
you had to put a photograph on
the folder of your application.

01:03:17.040 --> 01:03:19.700
So your looks are
absolutely part of the.

01:03:19.700 --> 01:03:20.780
Application

01:03:20.780 --> 01:03:22.490
So I think Korean
parents are kind

01:03:22.490 --> 01:03:24.680
of thinking-- even
though I just, right now,

01:03:24.680 --> 01:03:28.700
kind of indicted them,
let me defend them now.

01:03:28.700 --> 01:03:31.550
They're kind of saying, well, I
want my kids to be competitive.

01:03:31.550 --> 01:03:32.791
I want to be competitive.

01:03:32.791 --> 01:03:33.290
Right?

01:03:33.290 --> 01:03:35.927
So if you are an older man,
and you want to keep a job,

01:03:35.927 --> 01:03:38.510
and you're being discriminated
against for age discrimination,

01:03:38.510 --> 01:03:42.614
and you want to dye
your hair, fair game.

01:03:42.614 --> 01:03:44.030
You're trying to
pay the mortgage.

01:03:44.030 --> 01:03:45.220
I get it.

01:03:45.220 --> 01:03:45.800
Right?

01:03:45.800 --> 01:03:47.841
So if you're trying to
get a job, and you decide,

01:03:47.841 --> 01:03:48.440
you know what?

01:03:48.440 --> 01:03:52.610
They prefer to have
bigger eyes, bigger eyes.

01:03:52.610 --> 01:03:53.280
Let's do it.

01:03:53.280 --> 01:03:54.590
It costs, like, $2,000.

01:03:54.590 --> 01:03:55.700
Let's go.

01:03:55.700 --> 01:03:58.310
So in that sense, I think
they're not thinking,

01:03:58.310 --> 01:04:02.325
oh, it's because I want to
look like Gwyneth Paltrow.

01:04:02.325 --> 01:04:03.700
Because that's
often the argument

01:04:03.700 --> 01:04:04.720
that's given in the US.

01:04:04.720 --> 01:04:06.744
And I totally understand
their argument.

01:04:06.744 --> 01:04:08.410
But for Koreans that
are kind of saying,

01:04:08.410 --> 01:04:11.516
you know, I would just like
to be more competitive,

01:04:11.516 --> 01:04:13.390
I would like to get a
better looking partner,

01:04:13.390 --> 01:04:14.764
I would like to
get a better job,

01:04:14.764 --> 01:04:19.310
if better looks is what you
want, I'll give it to you.

01:04:19.310 --> 01:04:21.430
- So hagwon and then
to the plastic surgery,

01:04:21.430 --> 01:04:23.904
- Sure, yeah.

01:04:23.904 --> 01:04:25.570
- I think we're going
to have a couple--

01:04:25.570 --> 01:04:27.310
we have some time for questions.

01:04:27.310 --> 01:04:29.350
How much time do we have?

01:04:29.350 --> 01:04:30.220
About 15 minutes.

01:04:30.220 --> 01:04:33.700
So it would be great if
you could walk to the mic

01:04:33.700 --> 01:04:35.980
when you have your question?

