And we'll take you one by one.

01:04:40.490 --> 01:04:40.990
- Hi, Min.

01:04:40.990 --> 01:04:42.550
It's Ani Patel.

01:04:42.550 --> 01:04:44.050
So I was at Brown University.

01:04:44.050 --> 01:04:46.830
And they had these
mugs in the bookstore

01:04:46.830 --> 01:04:49.590
with great first
lines of novels.

01:04:49.590 --> 01:04:51.370
And I thought,
"History has failed us,

01:04:51.370 --> 01:04:52.780
but no matter"
belonged on there.

01:04:52.780 --> 01:04:53.950
That's such a great first line.

01:04:53.950 --> 01:04:54.490
- Thank you.

01:04:54.490 --> 01:04:56.650
- Can you just tell us
more about that line

01:04:56.650 --> 01:04:59.920
and where it came from, and what
the bigger meaning of that line

01:04:59.920 --> 01:05:01.900
was for you in the
context of that novel,

01:05:01.900 --> 01:05:04.270
how it became the thesis
statement, so to speak?

01:05:04.270 --> 01:05:05.020
- Thank you, Ani.

01:05:05.020 --> 01:05:07.030
So each of my works,
the first line

01:05:07.030 --> 01:05:09.200
serves as a thesis statement.

01:05:09.200 --> 01:05:12.250
So even my American Hagwon,
I have my thesis statement.

01:05:12.250 --> 01:05:14.140
I may actually make
a release right now.

01:05:14.140 --> 01:05:15.820
But to answer your
question, "history

01:05:15.820 --> 01:05:17.710
has failed us, but
no matter," I am

01:05:17.710 --> 01:05:21.370
arguing that history has
failed almost everybody.

01:05:21.370 --> 01:05:24.520
Because in order for history to
work, in order for historians

01:05:24.520 --> 01:05:26.290
to chronicle the
lives of people,

01:05:26.290 --> 01:05:29.220
they need to have primary
documents and artifacts.

01:05:29.220 --> 01:05:32.180
And if they cannot, they
cannot record that history.

01:05:32.180 --> 01:05:34.210
So it's not that the
historians don't care.

01:05:34.210 --> 01:05:36.100
As a matter of fact,
I'm always arguing,

01:05:36.100 --> 01:05:38.112
because I've interviewed
so many historians,

01:05:38.112 --> 01:05:39.820
they're among the most
enlightened people

01:05:39.820 --> 01:05:41.980
that you can find in the field.

01:05:41.980 --> 01:05:44.020
However, they can only
work with what they have

01:05:44.020 --> 01:05:46.900
because they have to
go based on evidence.

01:05:46.900 --> 01:05:51.010
That said, most of us
in the whole wide world,

01:05:51.010 --> 01:05:53.230
are not important enough
to leave documents

01:05:53.230 --> 01:05:55.900
or to have our lives
recorded in real time.

01:05:55.900 --> 01:05:57.580
And therefore,
how is a historian

01:05:57.580 --> 01:06:00.940
supposed to think about us,
those of us who are illiterate,

01:06:00.940 --> 01:06:03.280
those of us who
are less powerful,

01:06:03.280 --> 01:06:06.130
those of us who don't have
powerful connections or money?

01:06:06.130 --> 01:06:09.417
So I'm saying that history
has failed us, all of us,

01:06:09.417 --> 01:06:10.000
in that sense.

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:13.150
And also for us to be
missing that history

01:06:13.150 --> 01:06:15.940
is a loss for
everybody, not just

01:06:15.940 --> 01:06:17.560
for those who weren't recorded.

01:06:17.560 --> 01:06:19.030
So that was my thesis.

01:06:19.030 --> 01:06:21.910
But I'm also saying,
"but no matter."

01:06:21.910 --> 01:06:24.700
And I'm saying it as
a matter of defiance,

01:06:24.700 --> 01:06:26.890
because even though
people are not

01:06:26.890 --> 01:06:29.440
recorded, even though the
important people don't care

01:06:29.440 --> 01:06:32.830
about us, we still persist.

01:06:32.830 --> 01:06:34.720
We still try to
fight for our lives,

01:06:34.720 --> 01:06:37.090
and our lives matter intensely.

01:06:37.090 --> 01:06:38.019
So I'm arguing that.

01:06:38.019 --> 01:06:38.810
- That's beautiful.

01:06:38.810 --> 01:06:39.530
- So thank you.

01:06:39.530 --> 01:06:40.238
- Thank you, Min.

