01:08:55.550 --> 01:08:57.960
could we do this to children?

01:08:57.960 --> 01:09:00.479
Because you know, when they
start, like peewee football,

01:09:00.479 --> 01:09:02.560
they're four or five.

01:09:02.560 --> 01:09:05.260
So before we start
judging other countries,

01:09:05.260 --> 01:09:08.229
I think it's really important
to really rethink what we

01:09:08.229 --> 01:09:10.910
think is OK and what's not OK.

01:09:10.910 --> 01:09:14.140
So as for hagwons, I saw
really great things about them.

01:09:14.140 --> 01:09:16.029
And I also totally
agree with you.

01:09:16.029 --> 01:09:18.970
The amount of pressure
that these children face

01:09:18.970 --> 01:09:20.569
is absolutely unacceptable.

01:09:20.569 --> 01:09:23.830
And I do speak out against that.

01:09:23.830 --> 01:09:26.859
However, I think that to throw
away this entire concept,

01:09:26.859 --> 01:09:29.080
to throw away this idea
that you could have daycare

01:09:29.080 --> 01:09:32.529
for working-class
people that's affordable

01:09:32.529 --> 01:09:36.010
when the state
doesn't provide it,

01:09:36.010 --> 01:09:37.479
I think that's an
elitist argument.

01:09:37.479 --> 01:09:38.859
I do.

01:09:38.859 --> 01:09:42.387
So I agree with you that
when I see these kids suffer,

01:09:42.387 --> 01:09:42.970
it's horrible.

01:09:42.970 --> 01:09:46.300
But I've also seen kids
from many other ethnicities

01:09:46.300 --> 01:09:49.240
and countries who get
upset about the 90.

01:09:49.240 --> 01:09:52.300
So it's not just pathological
that Asian people

01:09:52.300 --> 01:09:53.890
have this problem.

01:09:53.890 --> 01:09:55.940
I've actually seen
this in many groups.

01:09:55.940 --> 01:09:57.130
So you're an educator.

01:09:57.130 --> 01:09:57.670
You know.

01:09:57.670 --> 01:09:58.630
But I love your question.

01:09:58.630 --> 01:09:59.130
Thank you.

01:10:03.567 --> 01:10:04.900
- Hello, my name is [INAUDIBLE].

01:10:04.900 --> 01:10:06.220
But I go by JY here.

01:10:06.220 --> 01:10:06.790
- Jay?

01:10:06.790 --> 01:10:07.290
- JY.

01:10:07.290 --> 01:10:08.240
- It's JY.

01:10:08.240 --> 01:10:08.740
That's good.

01:10:08.740 --> 01:10:09.040
I like it.

01:10:09.040 --> 01:10:10.831
- And then I looked at
the hagwon industry,

01:10:10.831 --> 01:10:11.920
actually, for a newspaper.

01:10:11.920 --> 01:10:13.660
But I'm in the
Divinity School here.

01:10:13.660 --> 01:10:15.860
So I'm going to ask
about that instead.

01:10:15.860 --> 01:10:19.020
So Presbyterians
are protagonists

01:10:19.020 --> 01:10:20.316
of Pachinko, right?

01:10:20.316 --> 01:10:21.940
And I've heard you
talk in an interview

01:10:21.940 --> 01:10:24.220
that being a Presbyterian
is important for you.

01:10:24.220 --> 01:10:26.816
And I'm wondering-- I'm
hoping Presbyterians

01:10:26.816 --> 01:10:28.690
will be protagonists
again in your next book.

01:10:28.690 --> 01:10:30.310
I'm guessing probably not.

01:10:30.310 --> 01:10:33.550
But even then, I
want to hear you

01:10:33.550 --> 01:10:36.460
talk about why Koreans love
being Christian, and then

01:10:36.460 --> 01:10:38.960
especially a Presbyterian.

01:10:38.960 --> 01:10:40.405
- Wow, it's JY?

01:10:40.405 --> 01:10:42.770
So JY's question, for those
of you who didn't hear it,

01:10:42.770 --> 01:10:46.460
is about my use of Presbyterian
characters, and also the fact

01:10:46.460 --> 01:10:48.140
that, personally, I
am a Presbyterian.

01:10:48.140 --> 01:10:49.190
And it's true.

01:10:49.190 --> 01:10:51.530
My grandfather is a
Presbyterian minister.

01:10:51.530 --> 01:10:57.260
He was a headmaster for an
orphanage school in Busan.

01:10:57.260 --> 01:11:00.890
And he taught orphans
who were repatriated

01:11:00.890 --> 01:11:06.230
from Japan who had lost
their parents from Hiroshima

01:11:06.230 --> 01:11:08.000
and Nagasaki.

01:11:08.000 --> 01:11:10.400
These were Korean boys
who were sent from Japan

01:11:10.400 --> 01:11:11.540
and went to Busan.

01:11:11.540 --> 01:11:13.520
And my grandfather
was the minister.

01:11:13.520 --> 01:11:16.880
So in my experience, my
knowledge of missionaries

01:11:16.880 --> 01:11:20.600
is not just of the vantage
point of a person of color,

01:11:20.600 --> 01:11:25.620
being angry at those who
want to colonize the savages.

01:11:25.620 --> 01:11:29.280
That is a point of view that's
absolutely true sometimes.

01:11:29.280 --> 01:11:31.380
There's a lot of
evidence for this.

01:11:31.380 --> 01:11:33.984
In my experience, I've
also seen missionaries

01:11:33.984 --> 01:11:35.400
do something really
radical, which

01:11:35.400 --> 01:11:38.220
is to teach women how to read.

01:11:38.220 --> 01:11:41.500
The education of
Korean women would not

01:11:41.500 --> 01:11:43.300
have happened without
the introduction

01:11:43.300 --> 01:11:44.590
of Western missionaries.

01:11:44.590 --> 01:11:48.407
And I think about that as
a very important value.

01:11:48.407 --> 01:11:50.740
I also think it's important
to recognize that Christians

01:11:50.740 --> 01:11:54.470
have had a very important
civil rights aspect in Korea.

01:11:54.470 --> 01:11:56.530
Almost all of the
major protests that

01:11:56.530 --> 01:11:59.590
were conducted in
the history of Korea

01:11:59.590 --> 01:12:01.990
were started by ministers.

01:12:01.990 --> 01:12:05.500
So before we start to think
of Christians as being jerks--

01:12:05.500 --> 01:12:08.470
and some Christians
are absolutely jerks.

01:12:08.470 --> 01:12:09.070
I know.

01:12:09.070 --> 01:12:10.100
I'm a Christian.

01:12:10.100 --> 01:12:13.870
So I talk about that.

01:12:13.870 --> 01:12:19.600
And I write because
the money's so good.

01:12:19.600 --> 01:12:22.780
[LAUGHTER]

01:12:22.780 --> 01:12:24.210
No.

01:12:24.210 --> 01:12:25.800
I write because I want to.

01:12:25.800 --> 01:12:27.090
I have these questions.

01:12:27.090 --> 01:12:30.560
And I have a lot of
questions about God.

01:12:30.560 --> 01:12:33.100
God vexes me.

01:12:33.100 --> 01:12:36.140
Like, I don't understand
God a lot of times.

01:12:36.140 --> 01:12:37.670
That said, I believe God.

01:12:37.670 --> 01:12:39.800
I believe in the
existence of God.

01:12:39.800 --> 01:12:42.320
And for all of us who've made
the decision that God does not

01:12:42.320 --> 01:12:45.110
exist, again, we know, all
of us who are enlightened--

01:12:45.110 --> 01:12:48.230
there are people that are far
smarter than me in this room

01:12:48.230 --> 01:12:49.910
about this issue--

01:12:49.910 --> 01:12:51.662
you have to make a decision.

01:12:51.662 --> 01:12:53.870
And for me, I've made a
decision that there is a God.

01:12:53.870 --> 01:12:56.970
However, I'm confused.

01:12:56.970 --> 01:12:59.910
And sometimes, through
drama, I get to figure out

01:12:59.910 --> 01:13:01.320
some of my questions.

01:13:01.320 --> 01:13:03.690
And the Bible is a work
that is very important to me

01:13:03.690 --> 01:13:04.710
as a source material.

01:13:04.710 --> 01:13:06.540
So I write about that.

01:13:06.540 --> 01:13:09.780
And we have to
discuss Christianity

01:13:09.780 --> 01:13:10.950
in American hagwon.

01:13:10.950 --> 01:13:11.682
It will appear.

01:13:11.682 --> 01:13:13.140
Because one of the
strangest things

01:13:13.140 --> 01:13:15.480
about going to all
these hagwons is

01:13:15.480 --> 01:13:21.650
that if you go to most hagwons,
they're very Christian-focused.

01:13:21.650 --> 01:13:25.370
On the walls, you'll see all
these Bible verses everywhere.

01:13:25.370 --> 01:13:28.660
It doesn't mean that they're
Christian, just that there

01:13:28.660 --> 01:13:30.200
are Christian influences.

01:13:30.200 --> 01:13:31.643
Thank you, JY.

01:13:35.980 --> 01:13:39.140
- Not made for the
vertically challenged.

01:13:39.140 --> 01:13:40.850
Hi, my name is Leah.

01:13:40.850 --> 01:13:42.910
I'm originally from Japan.

01:13:42.910 --> 01:13:44.900
Was born and raised in Tokyo.

01:13:44.900 --> 01:13:46.820
My father is a
Colombian immigrant

01:13:46.820 --> 01:13:48.740
who grew up in Queens.

01:13:48.740 --> 01:13:52.700
And my mother is a second
generation Zainichi Korean.

01:13:52.700 --> 01:13:55.160
So when I started reading
your book-- admittedly,

01:13:55.160 --> 01:13:57.440
I'm only about a third of
the way through Pachinko--

01:13:57.440 --> 01:13:59.510
- Colombia appears in that book.

01:13:59.510 --> 01:14:00.290
- I'm sorry?

01:14:00.290 --> 01:14:02.084
- Colombia appears in the book.

01:14:02.084 --> 01:14:03.500
- I'm excited to
get to that part.

01:14:03.500 --> 01:14:05.041
I'm sorry I haven't
gotten there yet.

01:14:05.041 --> 01:14:06.720
- I'm excited for you.

01:14:06.720 --> 01:14:09.777
- So one of the first things
I thought about three pages in

01:14:09.777 --> 01:14:11.360
was, like, the people
who need to read

01:14:11.360 --> 01:14:13.580
this are Japanese people.

01:14:13.580 --> 01:14:17.900
This should be one of
the main audiences who

01:14:17.900 --> 01:14:20.420
don't see Koreans as human.

01:14:20.420 --> 01:14:23.870
I feel like them being able to
kind of experience this book

01:14:23.870 --> 01:14:26.210
and relate to characters
that they may not

01:14:26.210 --> 01:14:29.240
see as someone that's
relatable to them,

01:14:29.240 --> 01:14:31.042
I think that's really important.

01:14:31.042 --> 01:14:32.750
So I looked for a
Japanese copy because I

01:14:32.750 --> 01:14:34.370
wanted my mother to read it.

01:14:34.370 --> 01:14:36.770
And I found that there
is not a Japanese copy.

01:14:36.770 --> 01:14:38.900
There's not a Japanese
translation of Pachinko.

01:14:38.900 --> 01:14:39.800
- Not yet.

01:14:39.800 --> 01:14:40.430
- Not yet.

01:14:40.430 --> 01:14:44.660
- So it's been purchased by
27 territories, I think, now.

01:14:44.660 --> 01:14:47.000
So it's going to come
out by Bungeishunju.

01:14:47.000 --> 01:14:48.857
And apparently,
it's in the works.

01:14:48.857 --> 01:14:49.440
- Interesting.

01:14:49.440 --> 01:14:51.530
OK, so that was one of
my first questions was,

01:14:51.530 --> 01:14:53.390
was that in the works, and can
I help you make that happen.

01:14:53.390 --> 01:14:55.490
- But most Zainichi Koreans
have been reading it in Korean,

01:14:55.490 --> 01:14:56.570
and that's already out.

01:14:56.570 --> 01:15:01.190
And that's by a publisher
called Munhak [KOREAN]..

01:15:01.190 --> 01:15:03.165
- So I think--

01:15:03.165 --> 01:15:05.540
yeah, so my original question
was, was that in the works.

01:15:05.540 --> 01:15:07.370
It's great to know that it is.

01:15:07.370 --> 01:15:11.780
But what do you think
is the main message

01:15:11.780 --> 01:15:16.700
that Japanese, non-Zainichi
Koreans, but Japanese folks,

01:15:16.700 --> 01:15:19.860
what message should they be
getting from your lectures,

01:15:19.860 --> 01:15:23.630
your works of writing?

01:15:23.630 --> 01:15:27.290
How can we bridge that gap
between Japanese and Zainichi

01:15:27.290 --> 01:15:29.090
Koreans through
fictional writing?

01:15:31.680 --> 01:15:32.415
- Oh, Leah.

01:15:32.415 --> 01:15:35.684
[LAUGHS] I like your question.

01:15:35.684 --> 01:15:37.850
I think it's an important
question because I believe

01:15:37.850 --> 01:15:39.830
in reconciliation and reunion.

01:15:39.830 --> 01:15:40.955
With all my heart, I do.

01:15:40.955 --> 01:15:42.830
And I believe that the
only way we can really

01:15:42.830 --> 01:15:45.290
think about other people
is through empathy,

01:15:45.290 --> 01:15:47.040
and that's hard to do.

01:15:47.040 --> 01:15:50.270
And one of the things that I
really hasten all of us against

01:15:50.270 --> 01:15:53.090
is to tell people what to do.

01:15:53.090 --> 01:15:54.410
I encourage.

01:15:54.410 --> 01:15:56.540
I try to create drama.

01:15:56.540 --> 01:15:58.540
I hope that you find
yourself in the story.

01:15:58.540 --> 01:16:01.500
I sort of joke that my agenda
in life is to make all of you

01:16:01.500 --> 01:16:02.000
Korean.

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:03.275
[LAUGHTER]

01:16:03.275 --> 01:16:05.150
Because I think that if
I can make all of you

01:16:05.150 --> 01:16:08.720
Korean that you would see
that all of us are connected.

01:16:08.720 --> 01:16:12.340
But I think that being
didactic doesn't seem to work.

01:16:12.340 --> 01:16:15.530
And I think that forgiveness is
a difficult, difficult thing.

01:16:15.530 --> 01:16:17.642
It's difficult for
everybody, especially

01:16:17.642 --> 01:16:19.100
for those of us
who've been injured

01:16:19.100 --> 01:16:20.960
and for those of us who injure.

01:16:20.960 --> 01:16:24.960
So again, I'm saying something
that's very "Christian."

01:16:24.960 --> 01:16:28.050
Whether or not people
like that, I don't know.

01:16:28.050 --> 01:16:29.320
You know what I mean?

01:16:29.320 --> 01:16:32.710
Because I'm really angry
about a lot of things.

01:16:32.710 --> 01:16:35.530
So sometimes I'm not in
a position to forgive.

01:16:35.530 --> 01:16:37.780
I'm still mad.

01:16:37.780 --> 01:16:40.270
But I tend to work it
out through my drama.

01:16:40.270 --> 01:16:41.800
But in terms of a
message, I don't

01:16:41.800 --> 01:16:44.560
think I have a message
about the Japanese.

01:16:44.560 --> 01:16:47.290
I do think that what
I have tried to do

01:16:47.290 --> 01:16:49.540
is to be honest
about the history.

01:16:49.540 --> 01:16:51.640
And that's the reason why
I do so much homework.

01:16:51.640 --> 01:16:55.360
I do a lot of homework because,
even though I may start out

01:16:55.360 --> 01:16:57.550
with a position of
an argument, I often

01:16:57.550 --> 01:17:00.520
find that my argument is
wrong in the face of evidence,

01:17:00.520 --> 01:17:01.540
in the face of reality.

01:17:01.540 --> 01:17:04.900
And this goes back to the
question of reality corrects

01:17:04.900 --> 01:17:06.490
preconception.

01:17:06.490 --> 01:17:08.170
There are many
Japanese people who

01:17:08.170 --> 01:17:11.830
are suffering in Japan
today because Japan

01:17:11.830 --> 01:17:16.700
has a myth of being a monolithic
nation, which it is not.

01:17:16.700 --> 01:17:17.730
As you know.

01:17:17.730 --> 01:17:19.440
- I am proof of that.

01:17:19.440 --> 01:17:20.870
- And you're proof of that.

01:17:20.870 --> 01:17:22.550
My husband is half Japanese.

01:17:22.550 --> 01:17:24.140
My son is a quarter Japanese.

01:17:24.140 --> 01:17:27.350
So clearly, I think it
would be preposterous

01:17:27.350 --> 01:17:30.680
for us to think that
Japanese people are evil.

01:17:30.680 --> 01:17:33.350
It's almost like saying that
anybody is evil if they've had

01:17:33.350 --> 01:17:35.190
any kind of colonial history.

01:17:35.190 --> 01:17:36.305
And that's silly.

01:17:36.305 --> 01:17:38.720
But what I do think is
evil-- because I believe

01:17:38.720 --> 01:17:43.710
in the existence of evil-- is
dishonesty about one's history.

01:17:43.710 --> 01:17:46.400
So I think that if we are
honest about history, then

01:17:46.400 --> 01:17:51.457
we can begin to
consider reconciliation.

01:17:51.457 --> 01:17:52.540
- Thank you for your work.

01:17:52.540 --> 01:17:54.850
I look forward to reading
it in Japanese too.

01:17:54.850 --> 01:17:56.380
- Thank you.

01:17:56.380 --> 01:17:57.475
- Hi, I'm Jen.

01:17:57.475 --> 01:17:59.080
Hi, Professor Gersen.

01:17:59.080 --> 01:18:00.430
- Hi.

01:18:00.430 --> 01:18:01.620
- Isn't she the greatest?

01:18:01.620 --> 01:18:02.119
- Yeah.

01:18:04.480 --> 01:18:06.050
I had a couple of questions.

01:18:06.050 --> 01:18:09.040
The first one is, if you
have watched Sky Castle yet?

01:18:09.040 --> 01:18:09.800
- Yes.

01:18:09.800 --> 01:18:10.480
- OK.

01:18:10.480 --> 01:18:11.600
I felt like--

01:18:11.600 --> 01:18:12.530
- It's a K-drama.

01:18:12.530 --> 01:18:13.610
- Yeah.

01:18:13.610 --> 01:18:15.680
- You would have liked it.

01:18:15.680 --> 01:18:20.260
And my other question is, who do
you think you're speaking for?

01:18:20.260 --> 01:18:23.800
Because your past
two novels have

01:18:23.800 --> 01:18:27.040
been about Korean immigrants
and Korean-Americans.

01:18:27.040 --> 01:18:31.090
And the issues you just
spoke of now during this talk

01:18:31.090 --> 01:18:33.880
are, you know, plastic
surgery and hagwons, which

01:18:33.880 --> 01:18:36.610
are very Korean Korean things.

01:18:36.610 --> 01:18:41.140
So I was wondering, do you
have an internal, I guess,

01:18:41.140 --> 01:18:41.950
perspective?

01:18:41.950 --> 01:18:45.940
Or have you drawn a line
about whether you're

01:18:45.940 --> 01:18:50.860
speaking about Korean-Americans
or Koreans, the people who

01:18:50.860 --> 01:18:52.610
live in Korea?

01:18:52.610 --> 01:18:53.240
- It's Jen?

01:18:53.240 --> 01:18:54.350
- Mm-hmm.

01:18:54.350 --> 01:18:57.600
- So I don't think
I speak for anybody.

01:18:57.600 --> 01:18:58.520
I don't.

01:18:58.520 --> 01:19:00.360
And I wouldn't take that on.

01:19:00.360 --> 01:19:03.510
That said, I think people think
I speak for a lot of people.

01:19:03.510 --> 01:19:05.430
And all people of
color, all women,

01:19:05.430 --> 01:19:08.310
tend to have the burden
of representation,

01:19:08.310 --> 01:19:10.350
which I think is kind of heavy.

01:19:10.350 --> 01:19:13.260
I find it to be
a kind of a drag.

01:19:13.260 --> 01:19:15.210
And I was just sort
of kidding earlier,

01:19:15.210 --> 01:19:16.830
but I work on speculation.

01:19:16.830 --> 01:19:18.430
So I work on spec.

01:19:18.430 --> 01:19:21.400
And that means, literally,
that I don't have a contract.

01:19:21.400 --> 01:19:23.600
So when I write
fiction, I write it.

01:19:23.600 --> 01:19:26.460
And if the publisher
wants it, they buy it.

01:19:26.460 --> 01:19:28.530
If they don't want to buy it--

01:19:28.530 --> 01:19:30.480
and I know very well--

01:19:30.480 --> 01:19:32.190
they say, no, thank you.

01:19:32.190 --> 01:19:34.480
I've had a lot of no thank yous.

01:19:34.480 --> 01:19:36.280
So I write it for me.

01:19:36.280 --> 01:19:37.090
And I write it--

01:19:37.090 --> 01:19:38.290
actually, my sister is here.

01:19:38.290 --> 01:19:39.480
My sister Sang is here.

01:19:39.480 --> 01:19:42.790
And people often ask, who do you
think of as your ideal reader?

01:19:42.790 --> 01:19:45.100
And I always say Sang because
Sang thinks I'm great.

01:19:45.100 --> 01:19:48.189
[LAUGHTER]

01:19:48.189 --> 01:19:50.230
It's really helpful to
have somebody in your life

01:19:50.230 --> 01:19:52.230
who thinks you're great.

01:19:52.230 --> 01:19:53.230
And she likes my work.

01:19:53.230 --> 01:19:56.140
My older sister, she always
reads everything I write.

01:19:56.140 --> 01:19:57.670
Very helpful.

01:19:57.670 --> 01:20:00.820
So I don't think I even
speak for my sisters.

01:20:00.820 --> 01:20:01.900
Does that make sense?

01:20:01.900 --> 01:20:03.520
But I do think of
an ideal reader

01:20:03.520 --> 01:20:08.650
who loves me and thinks that my
thoughts might have some value.

01:20:08.650 --> 01:20:12.160
Because Jen, you know,
you know that the world

01:20:12.160 --> 01:20:17.030
isn't waiting for women
of color to start talking.

01:20:17.030 --> 01:20:20.780
So we have to decide,
maybe we'll say something,

01:20:20.780 --> 01:20:23.900
maybe they'll hear us, maybe
they'll come on a snowy day.

01:20:23.900 --> 01:20:25.360
I can't believe it.

01:20:25.360 --> 01:20:27.360
But they did.

01:20:27.360 --> 01:20:30.070
So I encourage you to speak.

01:20:30.070 --> 01:20:32.360
And I wouldn't say that
you're speaking for me.

01:20:32.360 --> 01:20:35.764
But I would say that when you
do speak, it gives me courage.

01:20:42.580 --> 01:20:45.430
- Hello, my name is Sun.

01:20:45.430 --> 01:20:47.320
And I'm from South Korea.

01:20:47.320 --> 01:20:49.150
And I love to dance,
so you were right.

01:20:49.150 --> 01:20:50.736
[LAUGHTER]

01:20:50.736 --> 01:20:51.610
- I didn't hear that.

01:20:51.610 --> 01:20:54.880
- I said, I'm from South Korea,
and I love to dance as well.

01:20:54.880 --> 01:20:55.380
- Oh.

01:20:55.380 --> 01:20:57.914
[CLAPS]

01:20:57.914 --> 01:20:58.830
- So you were correct.

01:20:58.830 --> 01:21:01.280
- By the way, I
actually asked my son.

01:21:01.280 --> 01:21:03.851
I said, OK, I think I should
do some sort of, like, dance

01:21:03.851 --> 01:21:04.350
gesture.

01:21:04.350 --> 01:21:05.110
What should I do?

01:21:05.110 --> 01:21:09.420
And he's like-- he looked
really embarrassed for me.

01:21:09.420 --> 01:21:11.460
He goes, you could
do a shoulder roll.

01:21:11.460 --> 01:21:13.920
[LAUGHTER]

01:21:13.920 --> 01:21:16.960
So that was my
best shoulder role.

01:21:16.960 --> 01:21:20.220
- So I resonate with
your story in some ways

01:21:20.220 --> 01:21:24.060
because I also came when I was
young to the United States,

01:21:24.060 --> 01:21:25.770
at 16 years old.

01:21:25.770 --> 01:21:29.370
And I stayed here
since and studying.

01:21:29.370 --> 01:21:32.430
And now, I'm at grad school and
thinking more about my career.

01:21:32.430 --> 01:21:35.769
And I do see myself going back
to Korea at some point and--

01:21:35.769 --> 01:21:36.810
- Have you done [KOREAN]?

01:21:39.440 --> 01:21:40.810
- For a career.

01:21:40.810 --> 01:21:42.470
But maybe for [KOREAn] as well.

01:21:42.470 --> 01:21:43.310
- OK.

01:21:43.310 --> 01:21:45.040
It means military
service, sorry.

01:21:45.040 --> 01:21:46.310
- Did you ask if I have gone?

01:21:46.310 --> 01:21:47.030
- Yeah, have you gone?

01:21:47.030 --> 01:21:47.740
- I haven't, no.

01:21:47.740 --> 01:21:49.000
- How old are you?

01:21:49.000 --> 01:21:49.581
- 22.

01:21:49.581 --> 01:21:50.080
- 22.

01:21:50.080 --> 01:21:50.746
That's adorable.

01:21:50.746 --> 01:21:53.185
[LAUGHTER]

01:21:55.480 --> 01:21:58.810
And so as I'm thinking
more about possibility

01:21:58.810 --> 01:22:01.990
of me going back, and as a
social scientist, thinking

01:22:01.990 --> 01:22:05.470
about, I will study
about the Korean policies

01:22:05.470 --> 01:22:07.510
and Korean society.

01:22:07.510 --> 01:22:08.890
And you are precise--

01:22:08.890 --> 01:22:11.490
and I always have that
this sense of vulnerability

01:22:11.490 --> 01:22:15.550
and that because
I am Korean, but I

01:22:15.550 --> 01:22:17.440
don't know much
about Korean society

01:22:17.440 --> 01:22:18.760
because I've been in the US.

01:22:18.760 --> 01:22:19.570
You know?

01:22:19.570 --> 01:22:23.920
And I was wondering if you
also share that component

01:22:23.920 --> 01:22:25.919
of vulnerability in your story?

01:22:25.919 --> 01:22:27.460
Because you are
precisely doing that.

01:22:27.460 --> 01:22:32.220
You live in US for the
majority of your time,

01:22:32.220 --> 01:22:36.490
but you're writing about
Korea and Korean society.

01:22:36.490 --> 01:22:39.490
So I was wondering if you had
that sense of vulnerability

01:22:39.490 --> 01:22:44.700
in your work and how you have
navigated that, if you have.

01:22:44.700 --> 01:22:46.000
- I am very vulnerable.

01:22:46.000 --> 01:22:49.220
You could hurt my feelings.

01:22:49.220 --> 01:22:52.300
That's one of my problems is
that I'm constantly worried,

01:22:52.300 --> 01:22:53.740
and anxious, and insecure.

01:22:53.740 --> 01:22:55.840
I have actually used
the verb several times

01:22:55.840 --> 01:22:57.640
today of how I'm afraid.

01:22:57.640 --> 01:22:59.560
And actually, that's
actually an adjective.

01:22:59.560 --> 01:23:00.730
But I fear.

01:23:00.730 --> 01:23:02.800
I worry.

01:23:02.800 --> 01:23:05.890
And part of it's
because sometimes people

01:23:05.890 --> 01:23:10.090
try to make me feel inauthentic
because my Korean language

01:23:10.090 --> 01:23:12.160
skills are actually quite poor.

01:23:12.160 --> 01:23:14.794
And I used to feel
really bad about it.

01:23:14.794 --> 01:23:16.210
And now, I don't
feel bad about it

01:23:16.210 --> 01:23:18.342
anymore, like, not
even a little bit.

01:23:18.342 --> 01:23:19.967
Like, if you just
try to do that to me,

01:23:19.967 --> 01:23:22.732
I'll just be like, whatever.

01:23:22.732 --> 01:23:24.690
And the reason why I'm
saying this is because--

01:23:24.690 --> 01:23:25.949
and I'm being a little flip.

01:23:25.949 --> 01:23:27.490
But I'm being a
little flip because I

01:23:27.490 --> 01:23:30.190
want you to have courage for
whatever people try to make

01:23:30.190 --> 01:23:31.390
you feel inauthentic about.

01:23:31.390 --> 01:23:34.060
Because when people try
to make you feel ashamed,

01:23:34.060 --> 01:23:36.340
because they may have
expertise and you do not,

01:23:36.340 --> 01:23:39.130
you have to wonder, why
are they doing that.

01:23:39.130 --> 01:23:41.090
That's not encouraging anybody.

01:23:41.090 --> 01:23:43.860
And it's certainly not
an educational idea.

01:23:43.860 --> 01:23:46.270
Pedagogically, it's stupid.

01:23:46.270 --> 01:23:49.360
So one of the things I want to
encourage you to think about

01:23:49.360 --> 01:23:51.670
is that it's impossible
at the age of 22,

01:23:51.670 --> 01:23:55.060
or even at the age of 50, to
be an expert about everything.

01:23:55.060 --> 01:23:56.676
But I have figured out this.

01:23:56.676 --> 01:23:58.300
There are people in
this room right now

01:23:58.300 --> 01:24:01.360
who know a shit ton more
about Korea than I do.

01:24:01.360 --> 01:24:03.290
That's awesome.

01:24:03.290 --> 01:24:06.690
But the thing that I feel like
I can do better than most people

01:24:06.690 --> 01:24:12.360
is that I could feel more
and use that feeling more

01:24:12.360 --> 01:24:14.630
with my craft of fiction.

01:24:14.630 --> 01:24:16.940
And that's my little field.

01:24:16.940 --> 01:24:19.290
And I can try to do
that as well as I can.

01:24:19.290 --> 01:24:21.480
I don't know what your field is.

01:24:21.480 --> 01:24:24.890
But I feel like when
you do find your field,

01:24:24.890 --> 01:24:29.520
initially, you're going to be
stumbling, but that's normal.

01:24:29.520 --> 01:24:31.920
So my son is 21 years old.

01:24:31.920 --> 01:24:34.350
And very often, when he
feels like something is not

01:24:34.350 --> 01:24:37.410
going well, I think, well,
is it because it's difficult

01:24:37.410 --> 01:24:41.250
or if it's because
it's unfamiliar to you.

01:24:41.250 --> 01:24:42.540
It's a very different thing.

01:24:42.540 --> 01:24:44.881
When you start something,
it's unfamiliar,

01:24:44.881 --> 01:24:46.630
but it doesn't mean
that you're bad at it.

01:24:46.630 --> 01:24:48.300
It just unfamiliar.

01:24:48.300 --> 01:24:50.760
But I really encourage
you to find your field.

01:24:50.760 --> 01:24:53.110
And if people try to
make you feel ashamed,

01:24:53.110 --> 01:24:55.889
I want you to know that
it's their shame, not yours.

01:24:55.889 --> 01:24:56.867
- Thank you.

01:24:59.801 --> 01:25:02.015
- Hi, I'm Albert again.

01:25:02.015 --> 01:25:02.905
- Albert, what's up?

01:25:02.905 --> 01:25:03.985
- Good to see you.

01:25:03.985 --> 01:25:06.250
- [LAUGHS]

01:25:06.250 --> 01:25:10.150
- So I'm a second semester
senior and a lot of my thoughts

01:25:10.150 --> 01:25:12.550
recently have been about
my family and my parents.

01:25:12.550 --> 01:25:16.000
And my mother, as we
spoke, she owned a hagwon.

01:25:16.000 --> 01:25:17.620
And she spent--

01:25:17.620 --> 01:25:20.310
I don't know-- a lot of time
raising me, educating me,

01:25:20.310 --> 01:25:22.060
She spent hundreds of
thousands of dollars

01:25:22.060 --> 01:25:27.680
on me, when we didn't have
enough for anything else.

01:25:27.680 --> 01:25:28.521
- But you're here.

01:25:28.521 --> 01:25:29.020
- I'm here.

01:25:29.020 --> 01:25:31.780
So this is my question.

01:25:31.780 --> 01:25:35.260
As I graduate, and from
your experience as a mother,

01:25:35.260 --> 01:25:40.030
a daughter,
ethnographer, a writer,

01:25:40.030 --> 01:25:43.120
how do I say thank
you to my mom--

01:25:43.120 --> 01:25:44.100
[AUDIENCE AWS]

01:25:44.100 --> 01:25:48.209
--and tell her I
appreciate what she's done?

01:25:48.209 --> 01:25:49.000
- I'm going to cry.

01:25:49.000 --> 01:25:51.800
[LAUGHTER]

01:25:51.800 --> 01:25:53.100
Albert, oh!

01:25:56.404 --> 01:25:58.400
- That's so beautiful.

01:26:08.900 --> 01:26:10.260
She must be very proud of you.

01:26:21.400 --> 01:26:24.340
I think you did that.

01:26:24.340 --> 01:26:25.930
I think you should go tell her.

01:26:25.930 --> 01:26:28.640
All of your education
was so frickin' great

01:26:28.640 --> 01:26:30.060
that you made an author cry.

01:26:30.060 --> 01:26:33.042
[LAUGHTER]

01:26:33.042 --> 01:26:36.024
[APPLAUSE]

01:26:36.024 --> 01:26:37.515
[INAUDIBLE]

01:26:42.990 --> 01:26:43.960
- Hi, Min Jin.

01:26:43.960 --> 01:26:45.240
My name is Charlie.

01:26:45.240 --> 01:26:45.790
- Charlie?

01:26:45.790 --> 01:26:46.289
- Yeah.

01:26:46.289 --> 01:26:47.020
- What's up?

01:26:47.020 --> 01:26:49.076
- What's up?

01:26:49.076 --> 01:26:50.200
So I grew up in New Jersey.

01:26:50.200 --> 01:26:54.010
I immigrated from
Korea in fourth grade,

01:26:54.010 --> 01:26:56.970
grew up in New Jersey
as my family came--

01:26:56.970 --> 01:26:58.510
- Where in Jersey?

01:26:58.510 --> 01:26:59.560
- Bergen County.

01:26:59.560 --> 01:27:01.059
- That's the promised land.

01:27:01.059 --> 01:27:01.850
- That's-- that's--

01:27:01.850 --> 01:27:03.871
- No, I mean, if
you're a good Korean,

01:27:03.871 --> 01:27:04.870
you go to Bergen County.

01:27:04.870 --> 01:27:05.930
- Yeah.

01:27:05.930 --> 01:27:07.795
- No, my parents, we
were all in Queens.

01:27:07.795 --> 01:27:10.740
And then they made enough money,
and they went to Bergen County.

01:27:10.740 --> 01:27:12.340
- Yeah.

01:27:12.340 --> 01:27:14.050
Yeah, so I actually
grew up in hagwons.

01:27:14.050 --> 01:27:17.170
And yeah, I had a ton of fun.

01:27:17.170 --> 01:27:19.266
I was one of those
kids who just--

01:27:19.266 --> 01:27:21.640
so they wouldn't let you leave
until you, like, memorized

01:27:21.640 --> 01:27:23.300
200 vocab words a day.

01:27:23.300 --> 01:27:23.800
- Yeah.

01:27:23.800 --> 01:27:25.390
- But it was pretty fun
because I had my first--

01:27:25.390 --> 01:27:26.556
- I have a quiz if you want.

01:27:26.556 --> 01:27:29.410
[LAUGHTER]

01:27:29.410 --> 01:27:34.390
- So my question is, I realize
you're a person filled.

01:27:34.390 --> 01:27:38.380
I guess, you have
a surplus of jeong.

01:27:38.380 --> 01:27:44.240
And how do you explain that
to non-Koreans or Americans?

01:27:44.240 --> 01:27:48.410
Because sometimes I feel like
I also have a lot of jeong.

01:27:48.410 --> 01:27:51.110
A lot of people, I can't
really express what

01:27:51.110 --> 01:27:53.420
that jeong is to other people.

01:27:53.420 --> 01:27:58.170
So how do you kind of explain
that concept to others?

01:27:58.170 --> 01:28:00.712
- Tell them you love them.

01:28:00.712 --> 01:28:03.490
That's really what it is, right?

01:28:03.490 --> 01:28:04.450
It's a kind of love.

01:28:04.450 --> 01:28:06.880
It's a very complicated
and beautiful kind of love

01:28:06.880 --> 01:28:09.964
that you have through hardship
and through experience.

01:28:09.964 --> 01:28:10.630
And it's a bond.

01:28:10.630 --> 01:28:12.280
Because it's not just affection.

01:28:12.280 --> 01:28:14.261
It's also a bond and a covenant.

01:28:14.261 --> 01:28:16.510
One of the things that I
think is happening in America

01:28:16.510 --> 01:28:19.960
right now is that we have
so many broken covenants.

01:28:19.960 --> 01:28:20.500
Right?

01:28:20.500 --> 01:28:22.874
We have so many social contracts
that are being violated.

01:28:22.874 --> 01:28:25.510
And when people are so
upset, they focus on the fact

01:28:25.510 --> 01:28:27.070
that somebody broke a covenant.

01:28:27.070 --> 01:28:30.070
But they forget the
existence of a covenant.

01:28:30.070 --> 01:28:31.500
I expect something from you.

01:28:31.500 --> 01:28:33.100
You expect something from me.

01:28:33.100 --> 01:28:34.420
And then we have an exchange.

01:28:34.420 --> 01:28:36.430
But we also have a relationship.

01:28:36.430 --> 01:28:38.410
It's also happening
right now in South Korea.

01:28:38.410 --> 01:28:39.790
Because you have--
for example, I

01:28:39.790 --> 01:28:42.010
mentioned the elderly poverty.

01:28:42.010 --> 01:28:44.320
The expectation
of so many parents

01:28:44.320 --> 01:28:47.050
is that if I spend
all this money

01:28:47.050 --> 01:28:50.980
on this child for her education
or his education, then somehow,

01:28:50.980 --> 01:28:53.350
this child will take care of me.

01:28:53.350 --> 01:28:56.380
But of course, right
now, in South Korea,

01:28:56.380 --> 01:28:59.680
you have greater, greater
delay of employment.

01:28:59.680 --> 01:29:02.740
Because after they've
finished going to university,

01:29:02.740 --> 01:29:05.980
the number one preoccupation
of most young Koreans

01:29:05.980 --> 01:29:08.560
is actually to become
a civil servant.

01:29:08.560 --> 01:29:10.120
I don't know if you knew that.

01:29:10.120 --> 01:29:14.760
And to be a civil servant,
you have to take more exams.

01:29:14.760 --> 01:29:17.289
And these exams take a lot
of time, a lot of money,

01:29:17.289 --> 01:29:18.080
and a lot of delay.

01:29:18.080 --> 01:29:21.850
And if you get one,
your income is actually

01:29:21.850 --> 01:29:24.840
inadequate to
protect your family.

01:29:24.840 --> 01:29:27.750
So the child tries, right?

01:29:27.750 --> 01:29:31.290
But then the child cannot
take care of his elders.

01:29:31.290 --> 01:29:35.850
And then so you have half of
the elderly in South Korea

01:29:35.850 --> 01:29:38.810
live below the
poverty line, half.

01:29:38.810 --> 01:29:41.100
And I talked to an
economist and a fund manager

01:29:41.100 --> 01:29:42.690
when I was in South
Korea recently

01:29:42.690 --> 01:29:44.190
as part of my fieldwork.

01:29:44.190 --> 01:29:47.790
So I said, well, so John, why?

01:29:47.790 --> 01:29:51.420
Why is there so much
elderly poverty?

01:29:51.420 --> 01:29:54.110
He said, hagwons.

01:29:54.110 --> 01:29:56.330
If you take that
money of $300 a month,

01:29:56.330 --> 01:29:58.760
starting at the age of
four, you start putting it

01:29:58.760 --> 01:30:03.800
into, let's say,
Fidelity, Vanguard,

01:30:03.800 --> 01:30:08.810
some no load mutual fund,
then you might actually

01:30:08.810 --> 01:30:11.150
have an enormous amount
of money by the time

01:30:11.150 --> 01:30:13.170
the child finishes college.

01:30:13.170 --> 01:30:16.490
And his proposition was
actually to not pay for hagwons,

01:30:16.490 --> 01:30:20.270
to take that money, and
give exactly half in cash

01:30:20.270 --> 01:30:21.990
to your kid.

01:30:21.990 --> 01:30:24.740
And I thought, that
kind of makes sense.

01:30:24.740 --> 01:30:25.430
- Good idea.

01:30:25.430 --> 01:30:26.277
- Right?

01:30:26.277 --> 01:30:29.260
- Yeah.

01:30:29.260 --> 01:30:29.980
Thank you.

01:30:29.980 --> 01:30:30.980
Thank you for your time.

01:30:30.980 --> 01:30:31.556
- Thank you.

01:30:35.993 --> 01:30:39.150
- And thank you Min
Jin and to Jeannie

01:30:39.150 --> 01:30:41.670
for that wonderful exchange
and that wonderful lecture.

01:30:41.670 --> 01:30:42.270
Thank you.

